animal.description:
Meet Bo! 

Bo is a very special boy looking for a very special family to love him as much as he loves his humans! 

Bo was a typical dog before one random morning he woke up and could not use his back legs. He had 2 severe herniated disks that came on very suddenly. His previous owners were amazing and got him the surgery he needed to correct them but unfortunately, in Bo’s case the surgery did not take.  This left him paralyzed in his back end. He has had extensive therapy with both his previous owners and Zoe’s House. The therapist he currently sees says that he will continue to benefit from acupuncture therapy twice a month for the rest of his life. His previous owners were devastated having to surrender him but they had health issues of their own. They knew this sweet boy deserved the best in life.  Even if it meant they couldn't be the ones to provide it. 

Bo’s condition does not stop him from living his best life and loving everyone he meets! He has adapted to getting around and uses his front legs to move around the house and boy is he fast! He also has an indoor cart he can use (which isn’t his favorite) and an outdoor cart which he absolutely loves!! Bo loves being around people. He does have separation anxiety but it is being managed well with medication. Due to this he would do well in a home where someone is home most of the time.

Bo currently lives with his foster families fur children (2 dogs and a cat) and human children aged 2 and 6. He gets along well with everyone. If a dog is hyper/active he needs slower introductions. 

Bo does wear diapers or a belly band, for bathroom purposes, but he does have a routine with defecation so his foster mom is now able to get him outside to do “#2” most of the time. 

Please don’t let Bo’s condition turn you away from this sweet sweet boy!! He would do well in many different homes as long as he is given love and attention! We can also answer any questions you have if you are considering adopting this amazing boy! Due to his medical condition we are requiring children ages 6 and older. 

Please visit www.zoeshouserescue.com to complete an application.

animal.description:
Mylo requires a countryside home away from strange dogs and where he has lots of room to run around, with an experienced owner.

Hi there, my name is Mylo. I am 3 year old old labrador retriever cross.  I was born on March 20, 2017. I was found with my mom and siblings in an abandoned building in Tehran. The city officials were going to take us away and "dispose" of us. The ruling clerics in Iran consider dogs impure and it is even illegal to own a dog here. Thankfully a shelter here found out about us and stepped in to save us.

I had found a home here in Canada, but due to dog aggression issues my adopter has made the heartbreaking decision that she can't keep me. She thinks it is because of fear, since once I feel safe around another dog, I will play with them all day.

Why should you bring me home, you ask? Well, I am one of the most affectionate cuddlebugs you will ever meet! I'm a lap dog trapped in a big dog's body. I'd love to sleep on the bed or snuggle on the couch with you, if you'd let me (I only come up when invited). I'm also super smart and know a lot of tricks, and respect the boundaries that my family has set in place. Overall, I can be quite lazy and am happy to sleep the day away. That being said, I'm also happy to be your hiking partner, or simply go for car rides. I just want to be around you. 

I currently live with a cat but sometimes my instincts get the best of me and I try to chase it. So it's probably best if I live in a house without. I will also bark to warn you about the scary mailman, but will quiet down if you tell me to. I can also be a fussy eater (like most Salukis) and mainly like to munch on meat or raw food. On the rare occasion I will touch dry kibble, but only if it's mixed in with some tasty meat. That being said, my love of raw food can be a great training motivator! Reward me with hot dogs or chicken and you will have my full attention.

I'd be best off on a larger property out of the city where I don't have to encounter strange dogs all the time, since right now I have to wear a muzzle and harness on walks. When another dog comes in to my personal space, I can get quite aggressive initially until I know that I am safe. My family has made some progress on walks by distracting me with treats, but I still have a long way to go.

My unpredictable lunging and strength has caused sprained wrists and ankles, and my family is finding it harder and harder to manage me on walks. I absolutely HATE my muzzle and try to get it off by rubbing on rocks or bushes, so an experienced owner who knows how to work through these issues with me so that I don't require a muzzle is a must.

My current family says that I am a grateful, gentle soul. They also say I am athletic and graceful when I get the chance to run around in the forest off leash with no distractions or worries, and that my new owner will feel like they've won the rescue lottery as long as they are prepared to work with me through my aggression.

please see our adoption guidlines at www.lovedatlastdogrescue.ca

i am neutered, vaccinated and microchipped. My adoption fee is $500.

animal.description:
Imagine if you spent over four months living somewhere that truly stressed you out. Imagine if you spent at least four months in a row feeling anxious and fearful regardless of how much you were loved by others. This is adoptable Iris's reality. At the end of the day, the kenneling environment is very stressful to Iris; we cannot change that for her. We work hard to provide her with enrichment and extra time outside, but she still returns to her kennel. 

Iris arrived in mid-September. The anxiety she has developed from living for over four months in the shelter environment has created kennel stress. Iris's kennel stress has led to her being fearful and reactive sometimes when meeting new people, which leads to not many people applying for her, which lengthens her stay inside of the kennel, which only furthers her anxiety. Iris will need more than one visit to acclimate to you. Trust us when we say that once she knows you are a friend, she is the most loyal and loving companion. 

Iris would also be totally ideal for adults only who love training; someone who loves doing nose work, and/or spending their time at a dog training/agility club. She has an incredible ball drive, scent drive and work drive. Iris needs someone who is willing to give her time to decompress once she is home. 

Iris will take extra time and effort, but once she trusts you, she will do anything that you ask. She is such a great dog and has so much potential. She adores our kennel staff and volunteers and can absolutely develop that relationship with you. We could see her being the best hiking buddy and loving outdoorsy stuff.

Iris was surrendered to the shelter due to no fault of her own. Her previous owner loved her very much but was unable to continue to care for her. She used to live with a small dog in her previous home. Since Iris's stress levels have been increasing, her dog interactions have not been going as well as before. It is possible that down the road, Iris could live with another dog, but at this point she will need to be the only animal in the home. When she is outside, she focuses well on her handler and re-directs from other dogs; especially if there is a tennis ball in her sight!

Iris is a very intelligent girl. She knows how to sit, come, stay, leave it and "let's go". "Let's go" is the command that her previous owners said to re-direct her attention, go for a walk, or leave a room. She really listens beautifully.

Yelling in the home is something Iris does not like; she becomes uncomfortable. She sometimes resource guards her toys but will give them up for treats or another tennis ball. Teaching her to share would be great! When meeting new people, she does best with a very slow introduction. She has lunged before when she is afraid and we want to set her up for success in the future.

She is about five years old and is spayed. Please call (219) 872-4499 and ask to speak to Karen if you are interested in Iris.

animal.description:
Danna – Boxer mix – 4yrs. – Female (46 lbs.)

Introducing our sweet girl, Danna! Danna was roaming a neighborhood and was picked up by Animal Control. She waited and waited for her owner to come looking for her, but sadly that never happened. No worries Danna, we’re happy to have you with us and find you a brand new, loving home! This little girl is crazy fun and has a ton of energy! She’s active, athletic, and such a pack of muscle that she’ll guilt you into getting up and getting active! Danna has definite “Boxer energy” and will need a lot of exercise to keep her happy and her owner sane. ? She plays well with other dogs that can meet her activity level. She’s great with people, although she can play pretty rough, so her best fit would be in a home with teenagers or older. Danna is smart, stubborn, and very food motivated… she’ll do anything for a cookie – but who wouldn’t? She’s still learning the rules, but she does like to please and catches on quickly. She appears to be housebroken as she doesn’t have accidents in her kennel, but we’re not 100% sure. We do believe if she isn’t, it won’t take long to train her. She does well on a leash after the initial excitement of the adventure subsides, but at first pulls pretty hard – and did we mention she’s crazy strong?! Danna loves to give kisses and will give a quick run-by smooch without any notice. If this adorable girl sounds like she needs to be part of your life, please fill out an application to get the process started.

animal.description:
Please only send inquires to the email in this bio all others will not be answered. Please read the bio before sending questions - we answer all we know about the dog here.

Hi, My name is Ursa! I'm a loyal Sheprador who loves chasing bugs outside and long walks around the neighborhood. I'm a little nervous around new people, so I may take some time to warm up to you and your new home, but once I know you're my friend, I love to play. Hide and seek is one of my favorite games in the house. I'm very smart and know quite a few tricks, but might need a little more work on how to properly meet strangers who come to the house so that I don't seem so intimidating to new people. I'm fully potty trained and passed an obedience class when I was a little younger (I'm a little over 2 now)! If I get really excited, I like to run zoomies, so it's a good idea for me to have a large yard where I can run and lay in the grass when there is good weather. I've been raised with a small person, but since I get anxiety about new things and take some warming up, it might be best if there are only adults in my new home. I like most other animals I've met (though I will chase birds and squirrels), but please give me a chance to meet your pet first, since some dogs scare me. I don't usually hang out at dog parks since I'd rather be with my people where I'm more comfortable, but if I'm on a leash or in the yard, I love a good chase! I would love to find my forever home with someone who can work with me on my fear and give me lots of walks and snuggles. I get scared sometimes, but I am such a good girl and I love to learn and earn treats! I'm hoping I can find a loving family or person who can give me the love and attention I need. Ursa Adoption fee is $300 - obedience training is required

Obedience training is also required for all our pups. We understand with what is going on in the world that this may be a bit delayed. Please email us the completion certificate.

To apply to foster or adopt please fill out application at

www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/apply-to-foster-or-adopt

Thank you for completing the application. We are all volunteers and short on time, we will contact you back only if we have more questions or your application is approved and you will be invited to meet the dog. We apologize for not being able to answer everyone back.

For more information contact Kelly.V@HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

DOGS are in Foster Homes. There is NO shelter.

**Our companions MUST live in your home as part of your family.**We do not transport.

**See our website for more information. www.HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

All communication is thru email so please be patient with us. We are all volunteers and work full time jobs and have families of our own.

It takes anywhere between 3-7 days to process an application - the more complete the application the easier it is for us to process it. Please notify your vet that we will be contacting them and to release information to us.

ADOPTION PROCESS:

1. Complete this application
www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/apply-to-foster-or-adopt

***Everyone must submit an application - we only keep them on file for 1 month

2. Application background check, vet check, etc

3. Invitation thru email to meet the dog(s).

4. Adoption Contract

Waylon is currently living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet him.

Waylon is eligible for a foster-to-adopt.

Age: ~ 2 years
Weight: ~53lbs
Housebroken: Yes
Crate trained: Yes, does well in his crate. He has also done well with free roam.
Dog sociability: Friendly! Likes to play and gains a lot of confidence by being around dog friends.
Cat sociability: Not a match
Kid compatibility: No kids, please. (stranger danger)
Ideal living situation: Quiet neighborhood and adult-only household ready to take things slow as Waylon warms up to his new environment. He takes time to warm up to all strangers. He requires a backyard and a social, confident dog friend that can show him the ropes!

Waylon is one of the sweetest, most soulful dogs we've ever met. He loves to cuddle and be by your side. He has world class snuggling skills and isn't afraid to give you a little nudge when he wants more pets. He's a total mouth breather in his sleep which makes for many photo worthy moments. He grows confidence around other dogs and needs a dog buddy in his home. He is a playful, rough & tumble type of player with other pups. He loves to chomp on toys and eat kongs filled with wet food or cream cheese and is happy to entertain himself. He truly thrives with a backyard and loves to lounge in the sun for as long as you'll let him. Waylon is a real ladies man and can't wait to find a special one to share all the love he has to give! He will truly thrive with a patient adopter willing to take things slow with him as he adjusts to new people and surroundings. He's a very sensitive fella, but once he feels comfortable he is a total mush and will be truly one of the most affectionate dogs you've ever met!

His adoption fee is 300 and he is neutered, up to date on vaccinations, heartworm tested and microchipped.

She loves to do any sort of training exercise where treats are involved and is working on clicker training. She loves to be with her people and will make herself at home on your lap!

animal.description:
Hello,

My name is Spike. I am a young (1-3 year old) 50 pound pit mix.

I have been lucky enough to go into foster a home!  I am definitely a puppy at heart! I can be a little over the top but I love training and learning new things. My foster family has been working to teach me to stay focused and not be so excitable. I am making big strides with them. Since I can be a little much at times, if there are any kids in your home I would do best with 13 and above.

I am highly food motivated. Food grabs my intention instantly! I have been working on being patient and waiting for my food. I tend to gulp my food down real fast so my foster family got me a slow feeder to slow that down and savor the flavor. My foster family says I am doing so much better. I also will sit and take treats (or fruit) nicely when offered.

There are no pets in my foster home but I seem to like other dogs. I can be a little energetic when I meet new dogs. If you have another dog, we can do a meet and greet and see how we do together.

When my foster family leaves the house, I am crated. I do well in my crate. I go in with no issues and relax fast. Sometimes I even go in there to rest throughout the day...especially when the door is closed to the office(that’s where they keep my dog bed). When time for bed, I will put myself to bed in my crate. I do well sleeping in my there all night.

I love pretty much all toys and bones. I will give them up if asked. I can be a hard chewer and have destroyed a few toys so far. I can’t help having fun with them. I really enjoy a kong with peanut butter in it. My foster family says that keeps me occupied for a while. They got me a ball with plastic spikes on it. I do play with it but it’s not really a favorite of mine. Tug of war with a rope toy is one of my more favorite games to play.

I am doing much better with potty training. We needed some time to figure each other out. It’s not perfect yet but I am greatly improving each day. I will need someone with a little time and patience til we learn together what works best in your home.

I have gone on a few car rides so far. My foster family has a big SUV and I have needed a little coaxing to get into it. Once I am in, I am calm and sit back and enjoy the ride
 
I have met a few guests. That has been really fun for me. I do tend to get a little excited and want to greet everyone with a big hug. I am working on keeping my feet on the floor when guests come over. I am getting pretty good at it.

I tend to want to set the pace for walking... I like moving a little faster. Fast walking and the occasional jog has been fun for me. I’m working on healing and walking at a slower pace. I just can’t wait to get going.

I have learned sit and leave it really well. I love to hear the excitement in my foster parents’ voices when I do it right. Wait, stay, down, all down, potty, me first(through doors), and come I am getting pretty good at...hoping to perfect them real soon. I’d love to learn more and continue training with you in your home.

If you think we could be a good match and you are over 21 years old, send in an application for me at k9stray.com. My friends at K9 will be in touch.

I can’t wait to meet you!

~Spike

animal.description:
With a name like Theorem, you know this is a smart a complex guy. But it is unbelievably easy to love him! Theorem is one of our Classic Barkers, meaning he has been patiently awaiting his home for over a year. He was originally rescued from an abusive owner. He and a number of other dogs were kept outside in a dirty junk yard in Mexico until fate intervened. Theorem has always gotten along with other dogs and people alike, but had some neck and collar sensitivity that made him unsuitable for an inexperienced home or one with children. Theorem went into foster mid-July and he is doing incredibly well! Theorem recently had surgery to remove some rotting teeth, and it's like he has a brand new personality! Here is what his foster family has to say:

""Theo is a big, handsome, funny, sweetheart who is SO excited to show you all his new smile! He is feeling better every day since his big dental surgery (8 days ago) and we are noticing surprising positive changes in his behaviors that we think must have been related to his pain from his teeth. He used to be slightly unpredictable when we would touch his face and body - he would ask for pets but then might growl and we didn't know why. That is all gone now... he loves being pet by his foster pawrents ALL the time. He is already happier overall, and more chill than before his surgery. His breath smells good now, and don't worry, he still has lots of top and back teeth so he can eat solid foods soon. We are so sorry for all Theo had to go through in the past, but we are SO excited for him to hopefully find his fur-ever humans now that we can fully explain his personality, which is: He is loving, loyal, and fun! He loves walks, adventures, car rides, treats, his toys, his bed, rolling in the grass, being pet by his humans, cuddling in between humans legs, and finding the best backscratching bushes in the neighborhood. He can sometimes get territorial with his foster sister (TBL alum Koda) and we have to correct him. He would like an owner who is experienced with dogs and is able to provide consistent and positive reinforcement so he can continue to become the best dog he can be!""

Theorem is about 7 and a half years old (estimated DOB March 2013) and a great medium size of about 50 pounds. He is housebroken, crate trained, walks great on leash, enjoys playing with squeaky toys, going for runs, laying in his dog bed, and eating treats.

If you'd like to meet this pup, please visit www.thebarkinglot.net/adoptTo initiate the adoption process for this dog, please complete our online application by clicking below. Your adoption coordinator will respod to you via email once they receive your application: www.thebarkinglot.net/adopt

animal.description: Meet Platt! He is about 2 years old and is a Lab mix, likely with a couple other breeds. He is sweet and his butt wiggles in glee whenever he sees his foster mom. He loves to cuddle with his family but isn't so sure when visitors come over so would prefer a family where there aren't a lot of people coming in and out. He likes to give kisses and revels in attention. Platt is fostered with a Great Dane and Chihuahua. He seems to prefer the Great Dane and other big dogs over small dogs. Sometimes he can play a little rough and needs reminders to tone it down. He doesn't always like to share so has to be fed separate from his foster siblings. He also can be over enthusiastic on leash when he sees strange dogs and people and needs a dog experienced family that will continue to work on his socialization. He has been fine with cats until they run and then he eagerly gives chase. Platt loves anything with stuffing and is still figuring out the difference between stuffed toys and beds and pillows; he thinks it's his mission to pull the stuffing out of them all. Platt fell into some bad luck before Labs and More. He was hit by a car and arrived at our rescue with a broken hip. He will now be spending the next couple of months recovering from surgery and will be available in mid Feburary to start meeting families. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
UPDATE : Brody just completed his 2nd and 3rd Heartworm treatment today and is resting at home now. This sweet boy completely won over the entire vet staff with his wonderful demeanor .

30 more days of restricted activity and he will heartworm free ! Good food and good meds and this handsome boy is now up to 96 lbs, about 4 lbs less than his ideal weight, but at least his ribs aren't showing .

If you are looking for a gentle giant please check out Brody .

BRODY is doing well in his foster home although becomes anxious when she is out of the room. He is so happy to be safe again he has a bit of separation anxiety, which we are working with to ease.

Sadly, after Brody's first vet visit we learned his heartworm infection is advanced and his heart is slight enlarged . He has started the initial part ( 30 days of Doxcycycline ) and will have his first injection in early December. His risk of a pulmonary embolism from a clot of dead heartworms is much higher due to the level of his infestation.

ASR does the conservative treatment of 3 injections to allow our HW+ dogs the best possible chance for a full recovery and we will be doing the same with Brody.

For any adopters interested in him he will need slow walks and very restricted activity while going through heartworm treatment . Overall this will be about 90 days since he has already started the initial part of the treatment

Poor Brody found himself at an overcrowded shelter, not a good place for a Heartworm Positive dog......but when shelter workers sent out a plea for this good ole boy, we could not say no.

Once he has settled in we will start his heartworm treatment and help add some weight to his skin and bones frame.

Tonight this nice boy sleeps well on a soft bed with a full belly, thanks to wonderful volunteers .

More to come.

THANK YOU TUESDAY S. FOR YOUR SPONSORSHIP OF BRODY FOR THE MONTH OF DECEMBER.

If you are not yet approved to adopt from All Shepherd Rescue, please fill out our online application at www.allshepherdrescue.com. Our adoption fee is $350.00.

animal.description:
Zira is calling for all working breed experienced owners! Zira is a spirited, young Shepherd mix that was found as a stray in North Carolina. The vet estimates that she is between one and two years old. While we don't know anything of Zira's past, it is evident that she was not given the opportunity to learn what should be expected from a furry family member. This means she will need a home with leadership, structure, and balance. Zira will without a doubt make for a loving companion and an ideal adventure partner, but her adopters will need to understand that in the beginning that can only come with the balance of setting rules and boundaries for this headstrong girl. Zira is currently working on learning her doggy manners to assist her in being set up for success in her new home, and we definitely think she is a fast learner!  She already knows sit, touch, place, and heel.   She is also working on high ten, sit pretty, and even push ups!!  

If you are up for a challenge or have questions and would like to chat about Zira, send us an email to adopt@crcpa.org or submit an online application on our website. **Zira will require a fenced in yard **

animal.description:
Hi there! I am Franky and boy, I am a real sweetie! I am about 4 years old, 30 lbs, and a very affectionate boy who loves attention. I love to be with my humans, snuggle next to them, and drape myself over their lap. Nap time on the bed is my favorite cuddle time. I will need a home with fur siblings who are young and like to play, sometimes I can be a little rough when I play so a home with another dog who is my size and likes to play would be ideal. I do need supervision if I am with other dogs and we are all eating at the same time. I can get food aggressive, and will wander over to another food bowl if left unattended. I can also be a little jealous if another dog approaches while I am snuggled next to my human, although I am getting better about sharing affection. My current fur siblings are female and we get along just fine but I'm not a fan of having another boy dog in my space. Sometime before I got here I hurt my eye and I have lost vision in that one eye but it doesn't stop me at all. My previous family said I am a fence climber so I need a good, secure privacy fence to keep me from wandering. NO TODDLERS OR YOUNG CHILDREN. FEMALE DOG COMPANIONS ONLY. Franky's adoption fee is $375

Thank you for your support in our rescue efforts!If you are interested in any of our Boston Terriers or would like to be eligible to adopt a Boston Terrier through our rescue in the future, please fill out an application. It can be found at www.texasbostons.com. Click on the Rescue tab and then on the Adopt Now! tab. Here you will find our adoption requirements along with a link for an online adoption application. This will allow you to get on our list of approved homes so you can immediately adopt a Boston Terrier when it becomes available through Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas.

We are always looking for good foster homes. These homes allow us to rescue more Boston Terriers in need because we have a place for them to go until they are adopted. Please consider becoming a foster home for Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas. You can fill out a foster application at www.texasbostons.com. Click on the Rescue tab and then on the Foster Program tab. Here you will find our requirements for becoming a foster parent along with a link for an online foster application. This will allow you to possibly become a foster home for one of our little Boston Terriers in need. Thank you for considering the possibility of fostering for Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas!

Any and all Donations are always needed and welcome. Because BTRNT is a 501(c) 3, all donations are tax deductible. If you wish to donate to Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas, please go to www.texasbostons.com and click on the red "Donate Now" tab at the top left of the page. If you wish to donate dog food or any other item, please mail to:

Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas

PO Box 867376

Plano, TX 75086

If you have any questions regarding Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas please call 844-428-7776 and leave a message. Your call will be returned as soon as possible.

Thank you for your continued support in our rescue efforts! Help us Rescue The Bostons!

He gets along with other dogs but he keeps to himself and doesn't really play with other dogs.  He seems to prefer the company of human companions.

He is neutered, up-to-date on vaccines and micro chipped.  He is in the process of getting house trained and doing well.

NOT CURRENTLY AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION. SEEKING DALLAS AREA FOSTER ONLY AT THIS TIME
 

Ramona

Ramona is a 10 month old Pug who is having some neurological symptoms and health concerns. Her previous owner to her to some cheap vet in Mexico to do surgery on her head, not sure why, and she was left with a HUGE scar. She has an issue with the ocular pressure in her left eye. In addition she has HORRENDOUS dual ear infections complete with blood and puss . Her neuro symptoms are that she spins and spins and spins. We are hoping it is a bad inner ear infection but if not our vet will refer her to our neurologist at MedVet. She heads to the vet tomorrow.

This sweet girl has endured so much in her short 10 months and we are so relieved to have her as a High Plains PAW dog to address concerns and make sure she gets the care she needs. 

She's not going to be a "cheap" dog but she is 100% WORTH IT! If you can help us by donating to this sweet girl that would be SO appreciated!

This handsome boy is Pilot & he will fly his way right into your heart!! He's been through a lot in his short life and is just looking for a place to call home. He is a little nervous in new situations, but comes around pretty quickly, then he's just a sweetheart who loves people & is good with other dogs! While Pilot like kids,, we think a home with older kids would be best at this time as he is still learning how to properly play. He would also do best in a quieter, low-traffic home. He'd also love a fenced yard because he LOVES to run around, but it is not required. Pilot loves car rides and doesn't mind be the "co-pilot" and is a huge fan of sleeping in bed with you. Pilot currently weighs about 45 pounds and so excited to find his forever family!

If you'd like to meet him, please fill out an adoption application at www.ehrdogs.org & ask for PILOT BAILEY!

animal.description:
Looking for a hiking buddy or camping pal? Summer is your gal!

SUMMER is a 4-year-old Shepard/lab mix, 62lbs, with perky ears, soft coat, and outgoing personality. She was rescued from a Tucson shelter with her puppies who are all adopted now. Summer is a friendly, curious girl who loves going for walks, taking road trips, exploring new places, and finding the perfect spot in the sun to nap. She is a good combo of active and chill. Although she is good with other dogs, she mostly just tolerates them and would prefer to be the only queen in the castle, but she promises to be a loyal companion. No Cats, she chases and thinks it's snack time. She is housebroken, leash trained, likes car rides, knows sit, stay and come, and can easily learn more. She is easy to train, eager to please, and loves being outside, or by her owner's side. Summer is looking for a quiet home on the range with a large yard to roam, paths to stroll, and places to go.

animal.description:
Fosters needed! 

Resilient Hearts has partnered with several shelters across WA state to transfer animals from their shelters into our rescue. But in order to continue our work, we need more fosters to join our program! 

Resilient Hearts provides a kennel, food, leash, harness, and covers medical expenses for all of our foster families. All you need is a loving heart! Also, we offer several fostering options, from weekend sleepovers to afternoon hikes to long-term fostering. There is an option for even the most time crunched foster! 

Are you a foster rock star? Do you have experience with large breed dogs? Comfortable with animals with medical issues? Have a couch for an older senior dog to rest their joints? We want you! 

Sign up is quick and simple: Please visit https://911fosterpets.com/ResilientHearts/fosterSignUp to sign up now! 

Questions? Please email us at resilientheartsanimalsanctuary@gmail.com to find out more!

animal.description:
Vincente is a highly trainable and playful dog! He has been in training with Humble K9. Vincente is high energy and loves running and pack walks! He is house trained, crate trained, and dog friendly! His excitable energy can make other dogs uncomfortable as he is pushy and thinks every dog likes him. Humble K9 will give 2 free lessons on handling Vincente when he is in high excitable energy mode. His adopter needs to be in charge, and patient to show him that not every dog loves him like he loves them. Vincente needs to have a home where he has an outlet for his energy, an outdoorsy person, and someone who will take him on daily walks, runs, or hikes. This happy boy is great with kids and people! He is the perfect boy for a home with an active lifestyle! Please give this energetic boy the chance to be your best friend!

If interested in adopting Vincent, kindly fill out the application found here:  

https://www.ozzieandfriendsrescue.org/adoptions

In filling out this adoption application, I understand that Ozzie and Friends Rescue cannot guarantee that the dog applied for is yours to adopt upon completion of application. 

We also want to disclaim that all dogs are rescued so we cannot 100% know the exact breed.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Gus and I will be the loving protector you have always wanted. I was a stray but am now in a nice foster home where I’m learning how to trust people again. I bonded to my female human foster moms very quickly but am learning how to trust males - I am currently enrolled in doggie training school where they say I am a very good boy with lots of potential! I have been on several social outings to restaurant patios and I’m so large that everyone loves to pet me..I like it when they feed me chips off the table so I sit politely and wait :) I am very cuddly and would love to be a 'lap Pyr' or share the bed with you if you let me. If you think I’m too big I’ll prove you wrong. When I want to be petted I will give you the pyr paw but I’ll never try to jump on you. I do well walking on a leash most of the time. Sometimes I try to pull to chase squirrels but I’m working on this in school too. I have cat brothers in my foster home who I ignore most of the time but will chase on occasion, only if they started it first! I’ve met dogs and like to play but it takes me time to adjust before I am comfortable enough letting loose. I will need an adopter committed to continuing my training and understands that I am still learning!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
ROSIE needed a RESCUE/FOSTER/ADOPTER by 10/16 so that she did not have to go to a local overcrowded shelter...so with an amazing foster offer, we committed!!! OK, so this write-up on Rosie was so good that I borrowed it :) Here is her story:-Rosie was found as a stay on Oak Gardens Ave in Long Beach, MS. She stayed with a family while they tried to locate her owners but no one came forward. With Rosie being a senior the stairs at their apartment were just too much for Rosie and the family.-She is a senior estimated to be 8-10 years old (vet estimated at 6 years...we feel more like 8ish)
-Good with dogs and cats-Heartworm negative-Up to date on all vaccinations. Thought to be spayed, will confirm.-Tolerates the clinic cat with total calmness-Has seen other dogs at the clinic and did not care...she passed her dog test with flying colors!-Needs a home (foster, forever or rescue) by Friday since her stray hold will be up and she will not have a good outcome at a local overcrowded shelter!-Not positive on house training. She pottied forever with me today so knowing if she is at the vet clinic is hard since she does not go out as often as a dog in a home would.-SWEETEST GIRL! I met her yesterday and went and took photos of her today. She will literally just lay her head on you and not want you to leave!-Does well in her kennel at the clinic.-On Carprofen for arthritis.-Missing a few little spots of hair due to skin condition but meds are healing her up quickly (skin scrape was negative). Rosie will be arriving at her Alabama foster home on Friday, October 16th. Please check back to see how she is doing 11/30 UPDATE: As you can tell by the updated pictures, Rosie has settled right into her foster home :) She has put on some much-needed weight and is looking and feeling much better and she is enjoying all of the fun of ranch life. We are still working out some medical issues and are awaiting the results of her bloodwork recheck today. We will update on that as soon as possible.

animal.description:
FOSTER and ADOPTER needed! Scar now known as Colt has been owner surrendered and looking for a foster or forever home to bust him out of boarding! He is a sweet and active boy and we LOVE him!
From his previous owner:

'Hello everyone. We recently adopted this beautiful 2-year-old pure breed Siberian Husky from a family of trainers and rehomers on craigslist. He is a great dog for someone who has the time and experience for a Husky. He is house trained, vaccinated, treated for heartworm, and chipped! I also have those vet records on hand. His name is 'Scar' which was given to him by previous owners due to his past trauma of a bullet wound in his right cheek. He is completely healthy and made a full recovery. Very energetic. I mean that. He requires a lot of attention.

Why am I rehoming? In our situation as young, on the go, people, it is the right thing to do. I want to make sure he is with an owner that can train and discipline him further which has experience with more 'headstrong' breeds. He is also good with other dogs and LOVES people. He requires discipline and a true Alpha. That is something I cannot do for him.'

We are seeking an adopter for him with husky or other working breed experience and plan to be active and do training/mental stimulation with this smart boy. A 6' fence is a must for him. He is selective with which dogs he likes at doggy daycare so will be best as an only dog.
Colt is neutered, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Adoption donation is $250.
If you would like to meet any of our dogs, please fill out an adoption application on www.maxxandme.org
Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

animal.description:
Lily is a beautiful and smart girl, who will need a VERY specific home. Experience with the breed is very much preferred. She will need a home with no other animals, and children older than 12 years of age. Lily is on daily anxiety medication and will need to remain on them for the rest of her life. She will need an active home with a fenced yard for her to run as much as possible as well. She loves to play fetch and is treat motivated. We believe Lily was born in April of 2015.

All pets adopted from the Humane Society of Freeborn County will have age appropriate vaccinations, testing, alterations and micro chips included in their adoption fee! Fill out an app at www.freeborncountyhs.org. 

We do allow home trials with our dogs or cats to approved applicants. This is how we make sure your new family member is the perfect fit. We ask that you allow at least a month for your new pet to adjust to their new home. They will need that time to decompress. During this time we will provide counseling to ensure a successful transition.

Please review the basic adoption requirements listed on our site before applying. We take finding the right homes for our critters very seriously as they deserve nothing but the best! Please allow a week for applications to be processed.
If listed as (Currently in Foster) - these pets are not at our facility but are in foster care homes. They are available for adoption. Meet and greets are available with approved applicants only. 

If you have any questions feel free to send us an email at freeborncohumanesociety@gmail.com. Don't forget to check us out on Facebook!

animal.description: Neptune came to us at the beginning of September, 2020 from an upstate animal shelter that declared him "highly affiliative." He leaned in for petting, allowed all handling, and seemed to enjoy training. Neptune came to his handlers when called and then oriented to lean against them. He will need a little training for his tendency to jump up sometimes and to softly mouth his handler. Unfortunately, as is customary of many white Dobermans, he has some visual deficiency; in other words, he can see, but not as well as he should. White Dobermans also tend to develop melanomas (skin cancers) as they age, so ideally they should have a vet exam at least every six months to be checked and treated, if necessary. Neptune is about 3 years old and he weighs 72 pounds.

animal.description: Ace came to us from an animal shelter recently (August 2020) after being turned in as a stray.  He was strapped to the back of a pickup and his video set social media on fire.  No one ever came to the animal shelter despite the list of possible adopters that signed up for him so we were asked to come and pick him up.  Ace is probably around 2 years and absolutely full of energy.  He is strong, doesn't seem to have any training and he has energy to burn.  He will certainly need an active owner to help satisfy those needs so he can be more relaxed at home.  Ace is smart and we think he's a willing learner but focus is something he will need to work on.  He will need patient leadership to show him how to navigate the world.  So far, Ace has been a doll with people and friendly with everyone but we haven't seen him around children.  His energy level may be better suited to an adult home anyway or one with teenage-aged kids.  Overall, Ace is a great dog but he does not get along with other dogs.  He is reactive on leash and though he has responded well to strong leadership, he will need continued work if he is to be walked in populated neighborhoods.  He is ready for a new home that can give him what he needs to be the best dog he can be.
animal.name: Ace

animal.description: Charlie is a new rescue boy from an upstate animal shelter, received on October 7, 2020. He was such a ball of energy that his shelter sent him to us with two types of medications intended to slightly sedate him. We have found him to be overly energetic only when he's anxious about his surroundings. Initially we thought Charlie might not be good with other dogs, as their presence seemed to overenergize him, but he seems to want to engage with them in a positive way. The animal shelter people found him to be compatible with a large playful female dog he was introduced to. Notes from Charlie's ex-owner indicated that he does not like cats though, and that may apply to any type of small critter. He was given up by his owner because of a minor bite he delivered to a child in the home around the time of the 4th of July fireworks, which they believe may have been the cause of his anxiety. He comes when called and seems to enjoy toys. We think he's a fun dog to be around!

They call me Smokey....I am a neutered male Rottweiler mix about 3 yrs old and i weigh 66 lbs. I'm a very handsome boy, likely housebroken, well behaved and love spending time with my people. I'm a little head shy so I would be best suited in a home with no small children. I do like other dogs but I would prefer to meet my doggie housemate just to make sure we get along...stop in and see me soon....I'm available now! Adopting a dog from the Conway Animal Welfare Unit is a fairly easy process. The first step to adopting an animal is submitting an application. The application allows us to individually consider applicants and helps us to properly match our pets with new owners. We want to make sure that our pets are going to homes that are ready to provide for these pets long-term. Adoptions are $50 and this includes vaccinations, heartworm test, spay/neuter and microchip. As with any shelter animal, health is not guaranteed but we do our best to screen out those animals that are showing obvious signs of illness or disclose that information prior to adoption. All dogs are heartworm tested upon adoption. 

If you are interested in adopting a dog and you reside OUTSIDE the city limits of Conway and the dog is less than 12 wks old, the cost is $75 which includes a spay/neuter and micropchip. The spay and neuter can only be performed at Vilonia Vet Clinic or Companion Animal Spay/Neuter Clinic. If the animal is less that 12 wks and you live inside the city limits the adoption fee is $25 dollars and you receive a voucher for $120 to use at select clinics for spay/neuter. The other option is that you provide us with proof of a pre-paid spay or neuter at YOUR vet of choice.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting me please go to www.fureverunitedrescue.com to fill out an application. 

I am in a foster home in South Texas, and will be transported to the Pacific Northwest once adopted. 

Victoria takes a little bit too warm up and would do better with a seeing eye dog. She is right around 38 pounds. She is not believed to be completely blind and seems to have a little more vision outdoors. She loves toys and to cuddle on the couch. Victoria would do best in a calm household with another dog to help her build confidence in her environment. 

Note: Victoria went to an unknown home to have the above pictures taken. She quickly became completely comfortable in the backyard and downstairs. She never ran into walls and was able to navigate stairs. 

TOTAL FEES FOR ADOPTION:   Adoption Fee of $275 + Texas Sales tax of 8.25%  + $150 transport fee for a total due of $447.69. The adoption fee includes all age appropriate vaccinations (spay/neuter, microchip, health certificate) and the transport fee covers transport to the Pacific Northwest on the next available date).

TRANSPORT: Currently we have monthly transports. It will be up to the adoptive family to meet the transport to pick up your new family member. Please be advised that our dogs are adopted to their forever families prior to being transported to the Pacific Northwest. Unfortunately at this time, we cannot bring dogs for a typical meet and greet situation, due to the extensiveness of the transport distance and it being unfair for the dogs who are not adopted to have to make the trip back. 

Due to the number of requests that we receive on our puppies and dogs, please be advised that all adoption applications are processed in the order received. Once we send you an application, your place in line does not get reserved until your application is returned to us.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting me please go to www.fureverunitedrescue.com to fill out an application. 

I am in a foster home in South Texas, and will be transported to the Pacific Northwest once adopted. 

Victoria takes a little bit too warm up and would do better with a seeing eye dog. She is right around 38 pounds. She is not believed to be completely blind and seems to have a little more vision outdoors. She loves toys and to cuddle on the couch. Victoria would do best in a calm household with another dog to help her build confidence in her environment. 

Note: Victoria went to an unknown home to have the above pictures taken. She quickly became completely comfortable in the backyard and downstairs. She never ran into walls and was able to navigate stairs. 

TOTAL FEES FOR ADOPTION:   Adoption Fee of $275 + Texas Sales tax of 8.25%  + $150 transport fee for a total due of $447.69. The adoption fee includes all age appropriate vaccinations (spay/neuter, microchip, health certificate) and the transport fee covers transport to the Pacific Northwest on the next available date).

TRANSPORT: Currently we have monthly transports. It will be up to the adoptive family to meet the transport to pick up your new family member. Please be advised that our dogs are adopted to their forever families prior to being transported to the Pacific Northwest. Unfortunately at this time, we cannot bring dogs for a typical meet and greet situation, due to the extensiveness of the transport distance and it being unfair for the dogs who are not adopted to have to make the trip back. 

Due to the number of requests that we receive on our puppies and dogs, please be advised that all adoption applications are processed in the order received. Once we send you an application, your place in line does not get reserved until your application is returned to us.

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Jimmy Chew! I'm a very sweet, soft, cute and quirky guy! They say I am probably a Bassett mixed with maybe Shepherd or Collie, but my bark is more Bassett-like. I have huge ears with a long, lowrider body. I also have a white undercoat and diaper, so I am as cute coming as I am going! I am approximately 4 years old and 50 pounds. I am house trained, but I am really not a fan of my crate. I am not destructive though, so I don't really need it.

The more comfortable I get, the more loving and playful I am. I can be a little mouthy when I play, but in a gentle way. I will bark a little when separated from you because I really like to be around my people. My favorite people are adults and older kids...the little ones don't understand my quirks (12-years-old and up).

I can be picky about my dog friends. I've lived with a larger, female dog and we got along after slow introductions over time, but I really don't care for male dogs at all. I also don't like kitty cats. I'd be happy as a clam being an only pet. I pull a bit when walking on leash and get a little over-stimulated when I pass other dogs, people, or moving cars, so a fenced backyard would be really great for me. I love being outside!

I know I'm a quirky guy in looks and personality, but that's what makes life interesting! I hope to find an adopter who will understand me and love me for me.

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online at http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

*Some of our animals receive a high volume of applications, and we strive to select the best home for each animal. However, we have many wonderful homeless pets available.

animal.description:
To access the home page for our group, click on Southern Comfort Maltese Rescue which will take you to the map page.  Below the map is our logo and the link to click on to access adoption forms, contact info or to donate. ALL DONATIONS ARE TAX DEDUCTIBLE.

Adoption Fee: $250.00 for both


This is a mother and daughter bonded pair. Momma Zoe is 14 years old, weighing 11 pounds and Jelly is 12 years old, weighing 8 pounds. They are very bonded and will not be separated. Both are very sweet and do not act their ages. These girls are spayed and up-to-date on their shots. They both will be having dentals in early November and then ready for their new furever home.
 
Momma Zoe doesn't see as well as she used to but otherwise is a happy girl. She does get irritated when Jelly starts licking her eyes and mole tags. Jelly also likes to lick people--a llot! They like going outside but are mostly pee pad trained.
 
They are good with other small dogs as well as ignoring a cat in the foster home. They love to sleep with you or just take a nap as long as they can be with you. Jelly likes to play with toys and games including playing hard to get when its time to come in from outside. She also likes to go for walks.
 
They can not be in a home with small children. They both have some occasional coughing due to collapsing tracheas which is being monitored. They definitely do not like taking medicine.
 
They are enjoying life in Bristow, VA until their forever family picks them up!



NOTE: SCMR DOES NOT adopt to homes with children under the age of 10 years or homes with Electric Fences

Out-of-state adoptions are possible; however, the approved adoptive home is responsible for making the necessary arrangements to pick up their new little one.

animal.description:
This girl came to us when her time was up at another shelter. Noone came to claim her. There loss is our gain. 

Hazel we think is 8 months to a year old,  spayed female who has 
tons of energy. Due to her age she has alot to learn but is willing to do it in stride. She is very food motivated so training will be a breeze and a asset to her growth. She has learn to sit all on her own. She could use some leash training manners but has done remarkably well with what she has learned so far. As we have been working with Hazel things make her fearful and sometimes overstimulated. She is very insecure when it comes to meeting dogs so we think she would do best in a home with no other dogs. Cats are unknown at this time.  Kiddos in the home should be older. Hazel is working with a local trainer on her insecurities but will need someone strong willed to continue this with her. 

If you wish to meet Hazel you must have an approved application with us. Once your application has been approved we can then set up a meet and greet between you, your family, and Hazel. All questions can be directed to our email ( office@horseheadscommunityanimalshelter.com) or by phone ( 607-739-3945).

~~ COURTESY POST ONLY CONTACT INFO BELOW ~~

 Buster was found in a field along Hwy 67 about 5 years ago. He was placed as a foster with a neighbor who became a dear friend. I walked him and engaged with him daily until last year when we were approached by the mother of a college girl who wanted her daughter to have a companion that could protect her. We all thought it would be a perfect world for him but as a classic college sophomore she began to neglect Buster. Buster was placed with an inappropriate family and now he's back at DAS A# 0903632. 

NOTE: He is a very specific needs dog: NO cats, high fence and no young children, they make him nervous. He NEEDS: one or two adults who are active and can exercise him daily, ideally work from home or come and go often and can keep him on a good regimen. A home with a yard is ideal as he LOVES the outdoors. No cats! He has a high prey instinct. 

Dog & Cat Paw Salute to You

animal.description:
Hi, My name is Sugar Britches. My foster mom says I am a sweetheart, and it's hard not to fall in love with me when you look into my eyes.

I love people, and am friendly with all dogs. I love to snuggle, and get belly rubs. I am super curious of all new sounds and smells. I am a little afraid of the crate but I have been learning to sleep in it now. I was super scared of car rides but I am also starting to enjoy them too.

My foster mom says I am super athletic and I enjoy going on hikes too. Even though I like to be outdoors, l don't mind going on just short walks and just hanging around the house as long as I get some attention and snuggles from time to time. When I am super excited, I can jump as high as 5 Ft.

Also, you might want to keep an eye on me from time to time because when my foster mom is not around that's when I explore the kitchen counters for yummy human food. I am still a big puppy so I'm still learning the house rules but don't worry I am a sweet pup.

Overall I really am a great pup and I can't wait to meet my forever family!

	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)

If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interetsed in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility..

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

319-372-2274

animal.description: Introducing Elzar, a handsome house trained four year-old Labrador Retriever, Hound Mix. Elzar walks well on a leash and easily follows directions without pulling. Elzar knows sit, down, place and is very treat motivated. He is one smart cookie and is eager to learn new tricks! Elzar is crate trained, and can sleep in his crate overnight or be left alone in the crate during the day. This means that you can go run your errands with the peace of mind of knowing that Elzar is chilling at home. He can also be left alone outside of his crate as he is not destructive. Elzar is very calm and well-mannered and enjoys meeting new people. Elzar loves to lay next to and lean on his person. He will lay his head on your knee, lap, or arm. Elzar enjoys gentle, tender affection, and prefers to stay away from rough-housing after developing a trusting relationship. Elzar is a loving and gentle companion who would make a great buddy. Elzar loves to be with his people, either laying on the couch with them or relaxing in the sunshine in the backyard. He loves going on walks, laying in the grass, riding in the car, and having picnics in the park. When he gets excited, he bounds around, and his ears flop up and down in the most adorable way, he will melt your heart. Elzar can become anxious in a high-stimulus environment, so he would prefer a low-energy home with adults only, and preferably no other pets. It is possible he can share a home with another low-energy dog. Elzar would like a house or 1st floor apartment with no shared stairwells. Would you like a furry friend to share car rides, walks in the park and picnics? Come meet the awesome Elzar today!

animal.description:
MAXIMUS (male)
Breed: Lab/Shpherd mixAge: Appox 3 years
Adopter Experience: Intermediate - Advanced
Status - AVAILABLE

Maximus is the biggest, sweetest teddy bear of a dog you'll ever meet. He's social with other dogs, big & small, and is so tolerant of puppy energy. Great with kids, loves men and chasing birds. Poor Maximus was grossly overweight when he arrived from the shelter. We have gotten him town to a healthy weight and now he's ready for a home of his own to continue is health and journey.

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS & PROCEDURES

Mutt Match L.A. does not adopt out of state nor do we adopt on a first come first serve basis but rather to the home that is best suited for each particular dog and breed. An application, home check, contract and adoption fee are required for all adoptions. All dogs will be, or required to be, spayed/neutered, current on vaccinations and microchipped before adoption. Most of our dogs are from local LA area shelters, we generally have no prior history for them.

Adoption fees vary between $400 - $500 for puppies 8 weeks - 5 years, $350 6 - 9 years and $300 for dogs over 9 years. Adoption fee covers spay/neuter, vaccinations, microchip, a wellness check, any additional medical expenses necessary and of course all the love and daily care we take with each dog before they are adopted.

We believe a well behaved dog is a happy dog and companion. Therefore, we require at least one session with one of our recommended behaviorists for a reduced fee which is not included in the adoption fee.
We are a busy fully functioning rescue and facility, unfortunately, we do not take requests for more photos and/or video. The photos you currently see are what we currently have and are updated as we recevie new photos. For additional information or questions, please email us at info@muttmatchla.org. To submit an application, please visit us at www.muttmatchla.org. Mutt Match L.A. is an all volunteer rescue, please allow at least 48 hours for a returned response of all inquires.
Thank you! We look forward to hearing from you soon.

animal.description:
Action! Adventure! Comedy! Fun! This pint-sized pittie girl is the complete package! Her favorite activity is tug and her favorite toy is a tennis ball or 3 that she likes to carry all at the same time in her mouth! She lives to play with her toys! But China is also looking for a person to give her all to, to connect with, and to love. She's as smart as a whip, kid friendly and loves to go for car rides. While she is tolerant of other dogs, they don't hold a candle to a human's attention! We think she would prefer to live as an only dog.

Unfortunately her first few years of life were not very kind. She lived chained to a tree and was starved. This made her a little hesitant to trust other dogs and people, so she can be a little shy at first and sometimes reactive of other dogs when on leash. But once you get to know her, she's full-throttle fun and also a superb snuggler. She knows sit, down, touch, and high-five! She loves water, whether it's a kiddie pool or a river and somehow always finds the mud! If you're looking for some excitement and a dog who will make you laugh, look no further than China! For more information, please contact Shadow's Fund at info@shadowsfund.org.

animal.description:
Small dog... BIG personality! Tough boy Brandon... tough is an understatement once you hear his story! A few months ago, Brandon was badly injured and required emergency neck surgery. Because Brandon is now so fragile due to the hardware in his neck, he can never jump on or off a couch, chair or bed, in or out of the car, stairs... you probably get it. If his hardware gets compromised, they will not be able to fix it. Because of this painful experience and needing to be handled by many people, Brandon can be a bit sassy until acclimated with you and sometimes when being handled by those he knows too. Can we blame him though?

Despite what he's been through, Brandon is a feisty, fun and silly boy! He loves to play, especially with his balls and go for fun walks where he can explore everything! Brandon will protect you from intruders and keep your lap warm and heart full. He does well with dogs his own size, but no big dogs because they are scary, and no kids!

Do you think you could be a match for Brandon and are willing yo figure him out and follow his needs?

*We have an application and interview process. Completing an application is not a guarantee of approval. We do best fit for both dog and family.

NOTE: MARCY AND DARCY ARE FRIENDS AND BONDED SISTERS AS WELL. THEY MUST BE ADOPTED TOGETHER.

Adoption fee for both is $650 and includes spay, vaccinations, deworming, and pre-paid Home Again microchip.

MARCY is a friendly, 2-year-old, 50-pound, German Shepherd Dog and Hound mix, Sweet & good-tempered with a gorgeous red and black coat, this young and healthy mom of 7 pups is ready for a home of her own. MARCY is a wonderful friend and companion and would be an outstanding addition to just about any family! WHAT'S NEXT? If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY! Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date! *** This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives. Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. BY APPOINTMENT ONLY: Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins). An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals. Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please). This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times. Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details. To fill out an adoption application, go to: https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

animal.description:
Jordan Elliott is a dog in need of some rest, relaxation and TLC. He may not have had the easiest life so far, but he seems ready to start on his next chapter! Jordan is an active boy who seems to enjoy getting out and about to sniff and explore. He has a playful side and is friendly with people. He seems pretty overwhelmed by the hubbub of the kennel, and can be a little sensitive to sudden movements or loud noises - he would love a quiet, loving place to unwind and learn how to enjoy the good life of a dog. Jordan is around 3 years old and weighs 45 lbs. Jordan arrived at the kennel heartworm positive, so will need a place to rest and recover. We cover the cost of the treatment, he just needs someone to give him medication and keep him calm while he recovers from treatment. Please contact us for more information!

10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.

Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. You must schedule a meet with a dog in advance - we are not currently accepting walk-ins. Please look online first to see if there are any dogs you think would be a good fit for your home before scheduling a meet. To get the process started, visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog and fill out the form. One of our adoption counselors will get in touch to schedule and confirm your meet! At the kennel, an adoption counselor will introduce you and your family to the adoptable dogs, share information we know about them, and discuss our suggested ways for successfully integrating a new dog into your home. You are welcome to meet multiple dogs. If the dog you adopt is already fixed, he or she may leave with you that day - otherwise, the dog can go home after receiving the spay or neuter surgery.)

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog once they are in the home. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.

Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DAPPL, Rabies, and Bordatella vaccines, though you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.?

animal.description:
Have you met Kizzy?

9-year-old Kizzy was an owner surrender into Long Beach Animal Care Services and became a Frosted Face in July 2020. Kizzy doesn't like being reached towards and is bitey at quick movements in her direction. She is reserved and keeps to herself, but there's a whole lot of love hidden under that armor of insecurity.

One of our volunteers has a knack for connecting with reserved and snappy dogs. Of Kizzy, she shares, "Kizzy sadly gets overlooked at Open House. She will not run up to greet you, begging for pets, or jump up on your lap, but if you take a little time to get to know her and get down on her level, you'll find that she loves having her head stroked, and a good scratch behind her ears. Once you gain her trust, she will seek you out for scritches and hop onto a dog bed next to you and settle down for a snooze. She deserves a quiet home environment, and a person of her own to love."

We know a lot about what Kizzy is like in a home environment, because she went on two-week Frosted Fling! According to her Fling mom, Kizzy knows commands "sit", "down", and "shake"! She did well with the other dogs in her fling home, as well as ones she met on walks and at the park. Kizzy was potty-perfect in her Fling home and went to the door or whined to let her family know she needed to go out. Kizzy enjoyed many naps during the day and slept through the night.

We are looking for a patient and understanding family who would give a dog like Kizzy the time she needs to feel secure again. If you think that might be you, stop by to meet her during our next Open House!

Open House: every Saturday and Sunday 10:00 am - 1:00 pm

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Apply to become a family: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated 1/28/21 KG

- Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

His new owners also need to be at home most of the time because he loves to be around his people. Gator is very active, so a running partner would be great for him!

Gator is a very sweet, smart, obedient, lovable dog who just needs a place to call home.  Could you be his match?  If so, please email us at info@adoptagoldenatlanta.com and someone will respond.

animal.description: Meet Bruno Mars! Bruno has similarities to a Lab mix and is 2 years old. He was found abandoned on the streets in Mississippi waiting for weeks for his people to return. After a volunteer saw him waiting and waiting they went and rescued him. Bruno is around 60 lbs. and fully vetted. He is good with the dogs at his foster home and is so sweet. Since being in foster care, we discovered that he is farsighted and cannot see anything clearly up close. It does not effect his behavior, it's just something to be aware of that he does bump into things as he can't see them clearly. He will require a home with a physical 5ft or higher fenced yard as he has in the past tried to escape a shorter yard to go adventure and he was not able to find his way back. Bruno is house trained and walks well on the leash. Bruno Mars will due best in home with kids 10 and up and no cats, due to him not being able to see up close. He has a prey drive like most labs as he went after chickens in the fosters home. He is a total lovebug who enjoys lap snuggles. He LOVES to play. He will play with humans, dogs anyone willing to give him playtime. He is a bit mouthy when getting into play mode, but easily correctible by saying his name. He has so much love to give. Bruno Mars loves other dogs and we would love for him to go to a home with other dogs. His foster states that he rarely ever barks and is such a good boy. To apply to adopt Bruno, go to www.charliescrusaders.org

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Lab lovers, meet Melanie, a 1.5 year-old Black Lab mix girl who has a great disposition and sweet personality. She posed so seriously for the camera that her cheerful exuberance doesn't come through in her photos. You'll have to meet her in person to see what a true delight she is! We don't have any history on his lady as she came to us as a stray from an overcrowded county dog shelter but we've been impressed with her gentle demeanor since she arrived here with us to work on finding a permanent new home. Melanie gets along great with some dogs but doesn't like others. Given that she can be picky about her dog friends, she would do best in the home as an only dog. She has also shown leash reactivity around other dogs when out for a walk so would do best in a home in a quiet neighborhood with lots of space so she wouldn't have to encounter many dogs on a daily basis. Melanie also needs a kitty-free home. She settles down nicely in her crate for a nap once playtime is over and has had excellent crate manners in her foster home so may be housetrained too although we can't guarantee it. Melanie loves to go for a walk but does need to work on her leash manners as she likes to pull ahead to explore. She has done well with an Easy Walk Harness and that is recommended as she polishes her leash skills. With some daily practice, she's going to make an excellent hiking, jogging, or walking buddy for her new family. Melanie weighs about 55 pounds and her adoption fee is $325. She's spayed, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Melanie. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Melanie and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.
