animal.description:
**ADOPTION APPLICATION REQUIRED via our website Rarerescue.org**

ADOPTION FEES: Our Adoption Fees vary based on adoptability to help all of the animals in our organization. Please make sure to read the adoption fee below in the bio.

BREEDS: We are not breed experts. The breed(s) listed for each adoptable are best guesses or suggestions.

STEPS TO ADOPT:

Read the adoptable’s bio below, including their adoption fee

Read  ADOPTION PROCESS page under the "Adopt" section

Complete the  DOG ADOPTION APPLICATION (located on our website RARErescue.org)

*Applications will be attended to before general inquiries. We may or may not have time to respond to general inquiries if you have not submitted an application.

We understand that it is important to you to find the right fit for your family. We feel the same way! The application is important and necessary for this reason. 

All of our Adoptables are:

*spayed/neutered
*up to date on vaccines
*heartworm tested if six months or older (and kept on heartworm preventative and treated for heartworms if positive when entering our program)
*microchipped prior to adoption

BASIC INFORMATION:

Suggested Breed(s): Pit Bull Terrier/Border Collie Mix
Gender: Male/Neutered
Approx. Age or D.O.B: 10 months
Approx. Weight: 51 lbs (full grown)
Coat Type: Short
Good around most dogs: Yes; playful, submissive dogs
Good around most cats: Not yet tested
Energy Level: Medium/High
Fence yard may be required: Yes
Any other specifics:  We committed to help Elliot James out of a shelter that euthanizes for time and space with only minutes to spare. He is teen pup with so much life left to live, he begged for a second chance with his eyes and his huge, happy smile. One of the volunteers who transported him, gave him the name Elliot after her son that past away in a tragic car accident when he was hit by a drunk driver. She wanted to help honor him by sharing his name with this well deserving pup. His middle name was James. 

Elliot James is wonderful around the children in his foster home and has loved everyone he has met. He is a playful dog and would do best with a submissive female dog or he'd also do well as the only dog to receive all his human's love and attention. 

Will you be a Hero in Elliot James' story?

Visit our website/Click on Adopt to APPLY today!  RARErescue.org

Adoption Fee: $185.00



Please REMEMBER, All of our Adoptables are:

*spayed/neutered
*up to date on vaccines
*heartworm tested if six months or older (and kept on heartworm preventative and treated for heartworms if positive when entering our program)
*microchipped prior to adoption



PLEASE NOTE: We are a non-profit organization without municipal or government funding. Veterinary/Medical expenses are constant for an animal rescue. Our adoption fees not only help to provide vetting and care for the animal being adopted, but they also help to cover heartworm treatments and other treatable ailments that many animals, that would otherwise be euthanized, need in order to be made available for adoption.



Please understand that adopting an animal is a LIFETIME COMMITMENT to that animal and there will be veterinary expenses throughout their life that can often cost several hundreds, if not thousands of dollars (without pet insurance), especially without annual checkups and preventative care.  As a potential family for this pet you are responsible for their safety and that includes keeping them on your property.

***If you are not in the middle Tennessee area, transport can potentially be arranged to approved homes, depending on distance and local adaptability. We normally do not allow adoptions outside of 1.5 hours driving distance.

Thank you for choosing to adopt, foster, or aid in the rescue efforts of RARE!

animal.description:
AVAILABLE: **Please read entire bio before emailing or applying. Thank you!***

Bella is an 11-month-old, purebred, female, German Shepherd Dog who is available for adoption. She has come through a very long journey since she arrived in our care.

At 8 weeks old, Bella was hit by a car and surrendered to our rescue. What followed has been 10 months of hard work and dedication by her foster parents, caregivers and volunteers. Bella has had extensive medical and rehabilitation at Blue Pearl. She had an MRI and, most recently, full body X-rays to ensure nothing is hindering her from reaching her goal to be 100% mobile on her own.

Fortunately, Bella has never met a person she didn’t love. She is incredibly friendly and loving. Bella loves to greet visitors at her foster home and at the park or on walks. She also loves other dogs she meets, so a home with other male dogs or no other dogs would suit her well.  Bella also loves car rides.

Bella is at the point where she can stand on all four legs and is upright on all four legs for walking for short periods (as seen in the videos). She will need a dedicated home to continue with her down this path. Bella will provide her new home with tons of love and kisses and devotion.  It is the right time to find that perfect home for her.

https://youtu.be/fXt8SzbpQF8

If you would like to adopt Bella, please visit our website and apply today!

https://www.washingtongsd.org/adopt

Please note that we require a secure fenced yard.

Our hours are by appointment only. IF WE FIND YOU TO BE A GOOD MATCH YOU WILL BE CONTACTED typically within 72 hours. YOU WILL HEAR FROM US ONLY IF WE FIND YOU TO BE A GOOD MATCH FOR ONE OF OUR RESCUE ANIMALS AND OUR ADOPTION GUIDELINES/PROGRAM. WE MUST REVIEW A COMPLETED APPLICATION BEFORE A POSSIBLE APPOINTMENT IS ARRANGED. NO EXCEPTIONS. All visits with the puppies/dogs are by approved applications and appointments only.

* We reserve the right to refuse any adoption without justification and not all applications or inquiries may receive a response. *

Thank you for your interest in our rescue dogs.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. Here are some helpful tips:
•	All dogs listed on Petfinder are still available. 
•	Please DO NOT use the "Ask About Me" tab on this page. We DO NOT receive these inquiries.
•	We CANNOT move forward until we receive an application. Even if you're only interested, please fill out an application at mnpitbull.com. We will respond within 24-48 hours (M-F) after receiving your inquiry. 
• Adoption fees are as follows: 2-5 months old: $400, 6-9 months old: $350, 10+ months old: $250. This covers their Spay/Neuter, Vaccinations, Microchip, 4DX, Fecal Tests, and Housing Costs. ********************************************************************************************************

Here’s a quick rundown of Laken's Needs:
-quiet home with no kids
-no cats
-no shared walls/quiet neighborhood
-likes other dogs but you need to provide structure during a long introduction as he has no dog manners and does things other dogs do not appreciate
-an owner that understands stress signals/dog language
-an owner who can advocate for him and provide ongoing confidence and obedience training. We will ask for your experience and game plan on how you plan to do this.

IF you are still interested, read on to learn more!

Hi there! My name is Laken, and although I’m with Minnesota Pit Bull Rescue, I'm not a pit bull. What I am is a handsome adolescent Rottweiler! I came to find my way into MPBR after being picked up as a stray. The shelter said I was showing signs that I was really nervous so the great folks at MPBR got me into a foster home where I can relax and start to work on some obedience and confidence skills. My birthday is approximately 4/18/2020. 
I would love to find a family that will advocate for me and help me to build my confidence. I tend to be a little more unsure when meeting new people and prefer to meet them before they can meet me. (That means my owner doesn't let people approach me but rather has the person stand still and I sniff them on my own terms.) This helps to keep me from nervous/excitedly urinating in new situations (which I have done on occasion). Due to my insecurities, when meeting new people my foster believes it would be best that I live in a home without the chaos of children.
I also sometimes get overly excited when trying to share affection and sometimes give a little face punch vs just a nice lick... and the littles definitely aren't prepared or even equipped to work with that (I sometimes still take my foster by surprise with this). I'm not always the greatest at knowing personal space as well as boundaries or home etiquette, my foster says this makes me a little rude so I'm trying to gain a better understanding of what rude behaviors are and control them a little better! I am also trying to learn how to keep my frustration voice under control and can be somewhat vocal in my kennel at times when there are things going on that I want to be a part of.
A home that doesn't share walls and a home that isn't located in a busy area would probably be best. I've also shown a bit of a tenacity to quickly chase small critters that run from me so no cats for me please.
Dogs- well I have met a lot of them, and I LIKE all of them... none of them have liked me. I do things like chew on their legs, come at them full force, try to mount them, etc. (All the things that I shouldn't do when introducing myself to new friends). It is extremely hard for me to remain calm around them which I need to work on if I am going to have off leash time with dog friends. For now, I need to be on a leash when around other dogs.
I LOVE playing with several squeaky silicone balls in my foster home... although most of them don't squeak anymore, but they're still AWESOME!
I do well crating and am kennel trained. I do well going to the bathroom outside as long as it's supervised to make sure that I go to the bathroom as I don't really like to be outside alone and tend to turn around quick to head back inside. It is important than I am accompanied outside by my owner as I do tend to show barrier aggression. This happens both while I am in my crate and there is a new human in the home and while I am outside and new human walks by the fence line.
I'm a strong and growing guy who needs someone that's ready to help me develop confidence while also showing me guidance and boundaries through ongoing training. If you think you’re the person for me, please visit www.mnpitbull.com for adoption information as well as their online application.

Laken is our Dog of the Month for February. What that means is his adoption fee is waived. The normal adoption process will still apply (home check/reference checks/etc).

Hello my name is Hope and I am looking for my furever home. My foster mom also calls me ‘sweet lady’ because that is what I am. Super sweet and gentle even though I have not been treated well. I love my humans and I just want to hang out with them. I have a great disposition and love people. I tend to jump up when I am excited but with redirection I have been doing well not jumping. 
I am 6 years old and have a few health issues* that are being addressed currently. I am known as a blue nose. I weigh about 55 lbs. but am on the shorter side.  
I am an active girl that would do well with a buddy dog. I find the hamster very strange and intriguing and I really want to play with her, but mom tells me I can’t, and I leave her be. 
I love to play with toys and interact with people, but I also am able to spend time alone in my kennel with no problems. I sleep in my kennel at night, after being tucked in of course.
My most favorite place to hang out and nap is moms lap of course. I like to hang out with mom while she is working too. I am still learning the ropes of living in a house and interacting with people indoors. I have a hard time on the bed and snuggling I have not figured that out yet. I also follow mom everywhere. Mom is teaching me that I am not going to be left behind which has helped. 
I am currently perfecting my sit, stay, and shake skills. I am so eager to learn anything I am taught. I also am working on my leash walking skills. I was never taught properly on this and it is apparent. Mom is helping me with that. We work in the back yard mostly but that is because the weather has been so weird this fall and my toes are itchy, so mom doesn't want me being near the salted sidewalks.
I LOVE SNOW and I like to eat it! It’s like a cold splash in my mouth that I enjoy.
I have not been around cats, but I do have a foster brother dog and 2 kiddos that I have done very well with and that weird hamster thing in the cage. I sure would love to meet you and become a part of your family. 

*Medical notes- 
Hope came into the shelter in very rough shape medical wise. She had hair loss all over and a large lipoma (fatty lump) on her left back leg. She has improved greatly over the past few weeks and her coat is looking great! She does have allergy flair ups here and there. She is on Apoquel while we figure out her allergy issues. This may or may not be a long-term medication to help with allergies. It is approximately $65 a month. We also wash her feet when she comes in from outside as those are what bother her the most when her allergies do flair up. In the next few weeks, she will go into our vet for her spay and lipoma removal. We will send the lipoma out for biopsy, but they are usually harmless. We will continue to update her bio as more information becomes available.

12/21/20 Update- Hope had surgery Dec 4, 2020 to have two tumors removed and sent out to pathology. The pathology results on Hope's tumors came back as low grade mammary carcinoma. These particular tumors appear to have arisen from benign mixed mammary tumor. Carcinomas such as these tend to have a prolonged survival time. Based on her age and the prolonged survival time, we have decided not to put her body through the stress of chemo. Hope will hopefully have a few good years left but we do not know her life expectancy. We do believe she deserves a home of her own to spend her final days, months, years! 

If you’re interested in meeting Hope, please fill out an adoption application at www.mnpitbull.com.

animal.description:
Chachi is a 4 to 5 year old female Hound/Shepherd mix weighing 54 pounds. She sports a tricolor, medium length coat, and her eyes are deep and tell her story. Chachi’s owner could no longer afford to keep her and, as a result, Chachi’s life changed dramatically. Now she’s a dog in need of consistency to feel secure.  She’s an emotionally fragile dog who is playful and energetic but also worried when she meets strangers.  She’s quite intelligent, but also petrified of the vet.  She has lived with another dog, and yet she doesn’t like other dogs living in the same home, and she will not live with cats or small children. She will walk with another dog, but she must know the dog first.  She loves toys and must have a fenced in yard to help her with her high energy.  Are you a person with experience with dogs, who understands dogs, and who is willing to spend time reassuring this dog that she is loved and will never be given up again?  We mean this.  She’s wonderful girl who has been dealt a life of uncertainty. She needs you.  In-depth conversation with her foster will help both you and the foster decide if the adoption would be good for you and for Chachi.    (posted 9/4/20, HS)  (revised 10/13/20)  (revised 12/26/20, HS)

animal.description:
Scarlett is a petite pittie mix estimated to be about 6 years old with a unique brindle coat who came to us as a stray through Animal Control. A kind family had found Scarlett and tried desperately to find her owners but were unsuccessful. She had minor injuries and wounds from life on the streets, but she has since made a full recovery! 

Scarlett mostly ignores or avoids other dogs but does not mind calm and confident dogs. We don't know how Scarlett feels towards cats but could test her if you’re interested. Scarlett has met a couple of kids in foster care but has not engaged with them directly. Given her immature play style, we recommend she not go to a home with young children. 

Scarlett is as sweet as she is smart. Her favorite activities include watching TV, taking long walks/hikes, sunbathing on the patio, going for rides in the car, and being the perfect companion no matter where you want to go! Scarlett is crate trained, potty trained, excellent on a leash, and continuing to practice and master obedience commands. She is looking for a family without small children, where she can continue learning appropriate play behaviors, and feel safe in a home with patience, structure, routine and consistency. Ideally Scarlett will be the only dog in the home, but she can also be successful with a mature, confident dog. 

Scarlett loves being part of everything you do and has endless love to give her furever family. She thrives on routine with a confident leader, is a quick learner, and is desperate to please. While she may be 6 years old, she has the heart of a puppy and loves to play and explore outdoors. If interested in Scarlett, fill out a survey today at https://www.playersforpits.com/adoption-survey today!

animal.description:
Because we are all volunteers, Illinois Doberman Rescue Plus only considers approved applicants to meet our orphans in our foster homes. Please read our eligibility requirements and apply on our website: www.ildoberescue.com/adopt.  After an application is submitted, additional inquiries can email dobes@ildoberescue.com.

Mary came to IDR+ from our friends in Puerto Rico! Our vets think she is about 10 years old, and we are treating a long list of medical issues, so her adoption fee is sponsored through our Guardian Angel program. Mary has a grade 3 heart murmur, but the cardiologist said that she does not need medication at this time. The chest x-ray was normal--no heart enlargement or evidence of other concerns. Thanks to the SASS program at Vet Specialty Center, Mary was spayed and had 3 mammary tumors removed--you can see them in the "before" photos. The surgical interns got clean margins, and the lab confirmed they are benign. She had an ultrasound before surgery, and her spleen and lymph nodes show some enlargement, but nothing too concerning, so those will need to be monitored. One enlarged lymphnode was removed and also confirmed to be benign. In her foster home, Mary is a very sweet girl! She loves the resident Dobes, is housebroken, and likes her crate. She barks at the young neighbor kids, so she'd appreciate older kids (12+). Although Mary has a lot going on, there is no reason to number her days. If you'd like to be her Guardian Angel, she would love to spend her golden years in your home.

The biographical information provided is correct to the best of our knowledge while the animal is in our care or includes what may have been provided by a previous owner. We strive to be honest and accurate, but animals can change their personalities and behavior when they settle into a new home. IDR+ makes no guarantees based on the information we observe and provide.

animal.description: Bowie was originally a stray that no one came to claim. He is a sweet boy with a strong personality. Bowie was adopted and then returned because he was too much for the new owners. They were looking to make him a Service Dog and sent him to a trainer. After working with him, the trainer explained that Bowie's 2 breeds (Rottweiler and Husky) proved to be very stubborn and he would not make a good Service Animal. He is aggressive with other animals on walks and hikes and needs someone experienced with the breeds and the size. He is also still having some potty-training issues where he is peeing indoors, but luckily pooping outside. :) Now that we have the negative out of the way, you should know that this big, strong, boy is loving and affectionate and would make a great companion for someone who only wants one animal, has the room for him to exercise and is willing to be patient with him and willing to continue with his training. please submit an application first then make an appointment.

animal.description:
This glorious velvet hippo is Special! This 11 year-old, 69 pound, Pittie mix more than lives up to his name! 
 
Special is a fantastic fella looking for a mellow home to spend his golden years in. He’s been a little overwhelmed at our shelter (who can blame him!) but overall he’s an incredibly sweet boy. He’s very treat-motivated and will happily show you how well he sits in exchange for a delicious morsel! He really loves bully sticks and other tough chew treats that he can really work at! 
 
Special hasn’t shown much interest in toys while with us, but he’s very polite on his leash. Nothing goes unsniffed when Special is out and about! He still has good energy and would definitely make a good walking buddy. Special has let us know that he isn’t a fan of other pups, though. So he will need to be walked in quieter areas where there aren’t lots of other dogs out walking or behind fences in front yards. Special has been loving with the people he has met, but is a little shy at first. Once he warms up to you he’ll be leaning in for head pats and kisses! We recommend a home with no younger children for this beautiful beefy boy, he prefers a calm environment. No other pets in the home for him as well. Backyards and breed experience are both definitely pluses! 
 
Think you can give Special the wonderful home he deserves? Fill out an application below to make this handsome ham a part of your life! (CA)
 
Special is also looking for a temporary foster home while he awaits his forever one. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Rocket Dog Rescue is an all-volunteer nonprofit group dedicated to saving homeless and abandoned animals from euthanasia in overcrowded Bay Area shelters. We literally give them a second chance at life. And everybody deserves a second chance.

Adopting a rescued animal is a lifetime commitment! Adopters must complete an agreement (http://www.rocketdogrescue.org/adopt/adoption-application/) and a personal interview prior to adopting a Rocket Dog. There is a non-refundable $280.00 adoption fee which helps us defer the cost of spay/neutering, vaccinations and microchipping.
http://www.rocketdogrescue.org
https://www.facebook.com/Rocket.Dog.Rescue
http://www.petfinder.com/shelters/CA534.html

animal.description:
CHLOE IS READY TO BE ADOPTED 
SHE PREFERS A BACKYARD AND ANOTHER DOG TO PLAY WITH.
Not suitable for apartments  condos or small yard townhouses. 

Chloe has just arrived and learning to live in a home in a quiet residential area.   She is making progress but her foster mom feels she needs more time before she is ready to be adopted. We're estimating another 2 or 3 weeks.
***All applications received will be kept on hold***


COURTESY POSTING FOR KONGKONG2 SHELTER IN KOREA.
They don't have ability to solicit and process applications from Korea
so they have asked for my help. 



Name: Chloe

Age: appx. 4-5 years old

Breed: Jindo mix 

Gender: Female, spayed

Weight: 10kg, 22lb

Vaccinations: All vaccinations completed

Sociability: At first, she is cautious around new people and new environments. She cowers and retreats if people reach out to grab her. But if she’s left alone and kept in a routine for a few days, she quickly comes around and expresses affection and curiosity! Now she asks to be pet and cuddled, hops on the bed to sleep together, and is happy to see her foster mom after work. Right now on walks, she stops and hesitates a little when a crowd of people come toward her, but she is gaining so much confidence everyday!

Sociability with children: As a timid girl, she would get startled by kids’ loud and sudden movements, but she will eventually get used to things. We do recommend older children, over 8.

Sociability with other dogs: She is a peacekeeper with other dogs, but if other dogs show aggression, she knows to protect herself by barking back. 

Sociability with cats: Shows interest, but does not really socialize with cats.

Potty trained? Yes, she potties and pees in designated areas, but she still pees on blankets on beds if no one is watching. I am closing all bedroom doors when I leave the house. 

Separation anxiety/barking: She doesn't care if the house is empty and sleeps most of the day, but she has not been in a home without any other dogs, so we need to observe her in a different setting for separation anxiety. She barks at strangers coming into the house, but quiets down when shushed. 

Flight instincts? She can get startled if the person handling her is aggressive. But she does not instinctively run away from people or try to escape at her own peril. Rather, she freezes still if she feels threatened. 

Backstory: Chloe ended up at the shelter from street life. She unfortunately even got pregnant and gave birth at the shelter. Both of her children have been adopted, and Chloe’s since been spayed, but she was found with heartworm disease on the same day. She braved through the month-long treatment and is now finally heartworm free! In her short life, Chloe has gone through a lot. It is no surprise that before she got spayed, she was closed off and standoffish toward people. But after she got spayed, and especially after she lived with Mr. Tak, our shelter keeper, indoors daily, she has come fully out of her shell and learned to express her need for love to people. Now, all she needs is a forever family! 



contact adogsdreamrescue@cogeco.ca  if interested.
No phone calls please. 

Adoption fee  is $600
$400 Used  to cover her flight from korea

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 9/6/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Dexter was found as a stray by a staff member. His owners were found, but they decided to surrender him to rescue and help him find the right forever home.
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Lots of energy!!!!
Weight: est 40 lbs but he's low and compact - lots of good muscle tone!
Height: est 21 in at the shoulder
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? Dexter was originally brought to his home as a puppy but sadly, an accident sidelined his active family into a very sedentary lifestyle. Dexter needed more than they could give. They found a home but the home did not watch carefully and Dexter went a wandering for more action. He found Makayla, one of our caregivers with an affinity for bully breeds. She took him in and we were able to backtrack to find his first owner and get the whole story. Dexter s a young, active, playful puppy. He would love to have another active dog in his home but it's not a necessity. He would do well in a dog park setting to make up for not having a dog in the home.

Dexter is good with other dogs and cats!! He likes to hump other dogs sometimes but I think this is because he was alone when he was very young and he still needs manners with other dogs. He loves them but does not need to know how to play but he's learning. Dexter will need a fence in his home, young children are not recommended because he has a lot of puppy energy. He would love an active lifestyle with lots of walks and tons of play time!

What is my personality like? He does well on his leash but is pretty active so would need a stern owner to correct his pulling as necessary(works best with treats and positive reinforcement). Dexter does not like being told no!! He enjoys toys of any kind!! He is good in his crate and will start whining if he has to potty! He is mostly house trained and knows a handful of commands such as sit and down. We are working on more. Dexter can get too excited outside and jump up and nip at your arms, we are redirecting this behavior by giving him a toy when he does this. He can be mischievous and hunt down things to get into but this is only when he gets bored and hasn't had enough time to play! Also he is a weird pooper lol and likes to walk while he poops, so I always know if he poops inside because he leaves a trail

How do I act when I first meet new people? Friendly, affectionate and happy all the time.

Other tips and tidbits: Birthdate is 3/26/2020 est.

Dexter is very loving and loves to cuddle when he is all tuckered out!! Dexter is a puppy who is growing into a young man and still needs to learn a few manners and would love someone to understand this and show him how to be a good boy all the time!

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
Sweet Honey Love Muffin is a 7-9-year-old gal who is looking for a specific forever homelife. 

First, a bit about who Hun Buns is:
The folks that have helped Honey along her way describe her as a treasure. Honey has been in and out of homes and shelters her whole life but through no fault of her own. She has spent the last 3 years as a Montana gal in a home with multiple dogs and cats. She makes the perfect home office secretary and enjoys dreaming her day away in a cozy spot with a frozen marrow bone or a squishy squeak toy (kinda like a baby with a pacifier). While her legs are slow-moving, her tail is not. This gal cannot contain her love for you, life, and toys, and will show you how much she loves you and how thankful she is for you daily. 

Honey would fair best in a home without children. Kids are often unpredictable and Honey is looking for predictability considering her past life has been unstable. She loves having a cat sibling and could cohabitate with another mellow dog after proper introductions have been made. 


Secondly, her needs: While she's an easygoing gal in terms of personality she has mobility and allergy issues and will fare best in a home that she can have easy access to outside and doesn't have to accomplish more than a few stairs a day. She is currently on allergy medication - a simple pill once a day that costs around $30-40 a month. This medication does make her thirsty, hence the need to easily access an outside area. Honey enjoys short walks around the neighborhood but isn't a dog who needs exercise every day. She enjoys copiloting your car errands around town, sunning herself in a contained outdoor space, and really just being with you wherever you are.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: She has been fostered in homes with dogs and cats.

Lewis is 4 years young, 70 pounds. He is a handsome black and tan coonhound. He came to us from a nearby shelter. We got him neutered, all vaccines, dewormed and microchipped. He is energetic and smart - and responding well to B&B staff and volunteers who are interacting with him daily.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

animal.description:
Max is a 7-year-old Alaskan Malamute/German Shepard/Lab mix. Max has bounced around a couple of homes due to some behavioral issues but with the right family that is dedicated to him and his training, he is a wonderful dog!

Max will resource guard and is protective over his food, toys, and his person. His previous family claims he began this behavior after getting attacked at the dog park at the age of 2. The majority of the time he is a great dog with no issues, but he will need a family that is experienced and can work with him in the areas he has some issues. He is up to date on all shots, neutered, potty trained, crate trained, and walks well on leash unless he sees a bunny, squirrel, or another dog. 

Since Max can be protective of his person, Max needs a single owner home or a home with two very experienced and committed owners as he will likely end up bonding with and being protective of one of the owners. We will not place him in a home with multiple people (roommates) or kids. 

Max would do better in a non-urban area.  He's not a dog that can be left tied up outside a store and is a bite risk for strangers.  The owner will have to be vigilant about proper introductions. He's fluffy and beautiful, strangers and children will want to pet him.

Max should be the only dog in the home with no cats.   Max is a great dog and has a lot of love to give to the right family. His adoption fee is $450.

animal.description:
Rocky is a sweet 2-3 year old, 80-90lb Boxer/lab mix. He is looking for a loving and large breed experienced home. 

Rocky loves being with his people and especially bonds more with men. He makes a great lounge buddy but also enjoys being active and loves going to walks and adventures with his person.  

Rocky's previous male owner was abusive to him but he still loves males.  A quiet household is best for him.  He's loving and strong and doesn't know he's a big dog.  He can tip a person over with his enthusiasm.  A strong person to walk him is required.  

Rocky will need someone experienced with large breeds that resource guard, as he will guard his food and toys. He will thrive in a home that will work on training and structure with him.  

Rocky can do well with laid back female dogs but would also be great as an only dog. We do not recommend him with dominant males. No cats for Rocky.   Kids 12 and up (he's very strong and doesn't know how big he is)

Rocky is UTD on shots, microchipped and neutered. His adoption fee is $500.

animal.description:
Smokey is a 2 year old, approx 84 pound German Shepherd. He was hit by a car and had to have his eyes removed because they were so damaged. Call it tragic, ironic, unfair, sad... whatever your chosen adjective, the fact that this GORGEOUS DOG has zero ability to see himself or the world around him, is all the things.

And yet... Smokey listens. He learns so fast because he pays attention and figures things out. A raised bowl with a cone in a new environment/home? No problem. Show him once and he will get it. Like blind humans, Smokey learns his environment relative to his surroundings. He will need a home without chaos or clutter (no kids to be safe) and folks who understand things gotta stay where they are so he can learn to navigate his forever home. He's listening to and learning from the other shepherd in his foster home and must have a confident dog in his forever home. He's playing fetch right alongside her! Smokey has encountered several cats and appropriately ignored them. He is in foster with a handful of dogs and he gets along well with everyone. Smokey finds comfort in others. Humans, dogs, you name it, he's into it because you see Smokey HATES being alone. Imagine having NO EYES and ZERO concept of your spacial awareness... I would certainly feel terrified all the time, especially without the presence of a reassuring figure. Someone to guide using his other senses... it makes complete and total rational sense to us that Smokey would panic when left alone. That said, his forever home will need to be capable of dealing with this. He will scratch doors and panic when left. He needs someone with him to reassure him and love him the vast majority of the time. He's been through the wringer... this doesn't seem so much to ask... One thing Smokey absolutely requires is consistency. He needs a routine and he needs repetition. He shouldn't be in a home with stairs or where a pool could come into play. He wants a fenced yard and would GREATLY benefit from a similarly sized dog to act as his guide dog, one patient and loving, well-mannered and even-tempered so if Smokey happens to bump into them, they aren't offended or retaliatory.

Smokey needs a dadgum hero. He needs someone to just understand and love him because of and inspite of his hurdles. Someone who sees his scars as we do: a testament to his survival instinct and sweet, resilient nature. Smokey needs his family.

Smokey is neutered, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. He is heartworm positive and has started slow kill treatment. Adoption donation is $250.
If you would like to meet any of our dogs, please fill out an adoption application on www.maxxandme.org
Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

animal.description:
My name is Gucci. I am a handsome neutered 3 yr old American Staffordshire terrier (perfect blue boy ) and I am just now learning what it’s like to play with toys and how to get along with other dogs. I have been kenneled with my pittie friend Sadie my whole life. I am now with in a foster home . And I am so happy to be out of my dirty kennel. I am learning what it’s like to actually be a dog and have someone care for me. My foster mom says that I am a fast learner I just had no one to teach me manners so I do like to jump an because of my size I don’t realize my strength. So far I’ve been really good with low key calm dogs here in my foster home. I may have an issue with dogs that are super energetic because I don't know when to stop playing. I have a med energy level would do best with a family with older kids. I’d love someone I can play tug-of-war with and continue teach me what it’s like to be spoiled. I also like going on car rides and seeing the world. I’m doing really well on my crate training so that would make it pretty easy for me to be house trained. I will require a fenced in yard because I am so curious about new things! I do know that I am not good with cats because I will chase them. If you think you are the family for me, don't hesitate to contact us! And if you’re interested in a second dog me and my friend Sadie have gotten along so good please check her out also. We have known each other for the past three years and that’s all they’ve known in their kennel together. Don’t worry we will be totally fine if we are separated.

To schedule a meet n greet please fill out this form https://tinyurl.com/keelysadoptionday

animal.description:
Peanut Butter may come across as a bit intimidating at first, but that's just because being in a cage at the shelter can be scary for some dogs. 

During his enrichment sessions it's clear he's a big baby who loves to run and play. He wants an active home that will spend quality time outside with him, playing and running around. 

Peanut Butter is a young adult between 2-3 years old. He's about 50 pounds. 

He would be a best fit for a family or individual with direct dog experience. 
*****************************************************************************************************
Interested in adopting?

Due to COVID- 19 the shelter is closed to the public at this time.

We are still conducting adoptions, but with a few changes. :)

1. Submit an application through our website at wacshelter.com if you are interested in giving one of our shelter animals a home

2. We will schedule phone interviews once the online application has been processed.

3. If the animal applied for is determined to be a good fit for the home, we will schedule a controlled in person meeting with the cat or dog prior to the adoption.

*ADOPTION FEE:

$95 (cash only) and includes:

Spay/neuter
First vaccines
FIV/FeLV test (cats)
Heartworm test (dogs)
Rabies vaccine (if old enough).

*****************************************************************************************************
Additional questions?

Does this dog get along with cats? There is almost always an acclimation period when a new pet joins the household. We are happy to suggest a few ways to ease the transition. A new dog should never be left alone with resident pets though.

Does this dog respond well to other dogs? No dog loves every other dog. A proper introduction (meet and greet) would be required as part of the application process.

Is this dog good with children? The better question is how the children have been taught to handle animals. A dog will respond negatively if he/she is not being handled properly. We can offer suggestions on how to teach children to interact with dogs and pay attention to body language. Young children should never be left unsupervised with new animals.

*****************************************************************************************************
Want to help a real shelter animal by adopting a Mini Plush Pet from our limited time fundraiser? Check out our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/wacshelter/ for details!

animal.description:
Momma Brownie came form a hoarding situation with several other, related dogs. She was pregnant at the time, scared and under socialized. Since then, her puppies have been adopted, and she has come a long way in her foster home. To help with the transition to her forever home and make it a success, we are looking for a home similar to what she has now. 
-single family home with a fenced yard (she has a loud bark- too loud for a condo or apartment)
-at least one other young, playful dog (same size or bigger as long as they like to play)
- she also loves to play/snuggle with cats
- no children under 10 (she tends to nip at clothes or arms/legs in excitement)

Brownie likes to sit in people's laps and sleep in bed with them, but she is also great at going for walks and does several miles every day. She can easily gain weight if given too many treats or too much food and not exercised enough. Her love for other pets shows in the way she likes to play, snuggle and groom them. Of course, she also likes to kiss people. In the right home, Brownie will continue to thrive.
Email: dogs@almosthomefoundation.org

Almost Home Foundation's adoption requirements:
(1) Be at least 21 years of age;
(2) Have the consent of all adults living in the household;
(3) Have approval from the residence owner;
(4) Have valid ID with current address;
(5) Be approved by Almost Home Foundation as a suitable adoptive home; and
(6) Live in the Greater Chicago Land area. Illinois only
*** Please note that Almost Home Foundation accepts only cash or checks for adoption fees; we do not accept debit or credit cards. ***

animal.description:
Meet this handsome fella named Archie! He was surrendered over to the shelter October 8, 2020 when his owner could no longer keep him. He is 3 years old, current on shots, and just a beautiful boy inside and out. He walks very nicely on the leash and loves soaking up affection with his human friends. His owners said he can escape when he is left alone and can get out of a 8 foot tall fence. He wants to be with his people.  We were told he needs a home without other pets but Archie hasn’t been altered and if he interacted with other unaltered males that is very much a no go typically. We will spend time learning Archie and his likes and dislikes and update as we learn more. I can say he is a sweet sweet and handsome boy who seems a little starved for love and affection. Maybe you have the most am amazing FOREVER home for Archie?! 
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting another potential new furry member please bring him or her to the shelter and meet on neutral ground before adopting. No need to shuffle the animals around any more than necessary. Please know that 1 mosquito bite can create heart worms and they can be fatal if not treated. It is VERY important to keep your pets healthy and protected by keeping them on a once a month heart worm and flea/tick prevention. These animals are counting on you as their owner to provide them with lots a love and the proper health care so PLEASE make sure you are aware and prepared before adopting. Owning a pet is an extra expense and responsibility but is so worth every minute and penny you invest in them. They will add lots of joy and unconditional love if given a fair chance.
The shelter is open Mon.-Fri. 10-1, 2-5 and Sat. 10-4. Adopt a homeless pet and save a life. If you can not adopt right now come out and volunteer and make a difference in the lives of these animals while they await their FOREVER home.

animal.description: Agnes was relinquished to us because she didn't get along with the other dog in the house. This beauty queen is blind, diabetic, slightly hearing impaired and a couple of pounds overweight. Despite her ailments, Agnes is about as strong and confident as they come. Although she still bumps into things here and there, she pretty much mapped out her new digs in a matter of a few days. With the weight she's carrying, she's got a fancy little sashay when she walks that, truth be told, entertains the staff. For her health's sake though, we have her on the ever-successful Pug Nation diet. Agnes is full of life and isn't afraid of anything. We've found that she does get along with other dogs, but because she can't see, tiffs have broken out because she runs into them....and she's not one to back down. Once she has ""claimed"" her human, she's extremely loyal and prefers not to share the attention. She adores endless belly rubs and gives lots of kisses. Agnes does come with a list of health issues, but she is definitely worth the extra effort to care for her. Please consider this sassy senior as your next forever friend.

animal.description: Sweet Europa has maintained her positive attitude in spite of everything life has thrown at her. This 2 year old little mama is a Terrier mix and only weighs about 25 lbs. Europa came to Labs and More with her 6 puppies. One of her ears had been torn off and both her back knees had been broken. In spite of her pain, she took great care of her babies and now she is safe and getting the medical treatment she needs. She will be ready in December once she is finished recovering from surgery. She has a gentle, affectionate demeanor. She is good with other dogs and even gets along with the cats. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting Europa when she is ready for adoption, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! If you are already approved with a coach or have adopted from us before, please reach out to your coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported, solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description: Rex is about 65 pounds and about 5 years old. He is good around dogs and cats. He is sweet and a new arrival. He is a new arrival so more to come or email us at codysfriendsrescue.com He is heart worm positive but he is currently under treatment. Beautiful boy.He is estimated to be 5 years old. He was found on a busy street and when the finder opened up her car door he jumped right in. He is not interested in being in charge. He's an easy dog. Want to go for a leisurely stroll, Rex will be happy to join you. (Hes great on a leash.) Want to binge a show, he'd love to nap on the couch with you. While his foster mom WFH, he looks out for squirrels and neighbors, sleeps, and patrols the house, checking in for pets along the way. He gets along fine with adult dogs, cats, puppies, men, and women, although he is mostly apathetic to other dogs and doesn't engage in much play. (He hasn't been exposed to kids. Due to his past, a home without young children is best.) He's not easily concerned; he has little reaction to the vacuum, cars, or fireworks. He was found on a busy street and when the finder opened up her car door he jumped right in. He is 9 weeks into heartworm treatment and is doing great! Anytime we are out he gets compliments on what a good looking and acting boy he is. He's never had an accident in the house and has been home alone for 8 hours with no destruction!

animal.description:
Bug is a loving, big boy at 72 lbs. He is a  3-4-year-old lapdog (says him  ; ) who wants nothing more than to be held, cuddled, pet, and loved on. He is smart, loyal, and good-natured. Bug was surrendered to animal control because owners didn't want to pay to get his severe medical issue treated. He had that surgery after he came to us and he is fully healed and ready for a home and family.

He is housetrained and knows how to sit, stay, and shake. He could use some work walking on a leash. Bug is friendly with most other dogs.  He does really well with female dogs and all little dogs, male or female.  He has had some issues with large male dogs and intact males.  For this reason Bug will need to have a network of dogs to interact, hang and play with. He's not a good prospect for dog parks. He'd much prefer playdates with his pals.

Because of his size, he needs a home with a ample-size fenced-in spot to run around–hopefully with you! When he's had the right amount of activity, he'll snuggle up on the couch next to you (his favorite activity).

He also needs a home with no cats (no exceptions). He'd do well in a family with older children.

Bug's big smile and warm heart will surely make any dog lover melt. Does this sound like you?

Bug's adoption fee includes spay/neuter, basic vaccinations, rabies vaccination, and heartworm tested negative.

Questions? Contact us at connellpetrescue@gmail.com 

Thank you! And Bug thanks you!

https://forms.gle/5eSBjHrWv7pTEEzUA

She is a gentle giant but isn't aware of her size and can get very excited. For that reason she needs to be in a home with children 10 years and older. 

Penny is eager to please and does great without a crate and has been non destructive and doesn't have any accidents. She does not do well in a crate and she panics.

Penny has been through so much and we would just love to give her a happily ever after new beginning.

animal.description:
****Please do not send us inquiries/emails asking if this dog is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. See the bottom of this bio for more FAQs regarding our adoption process before emailing.****

Most of River's story is unknown. She was found as a stray with a belt wrapped around her neck that was used as a collar. She is one of the sweetest dogs we have come across. River is a bit shy at first but is very affectionate and loving to  people once she feels comfortable, which doesn't take very long at all!  She is full of energy, loves to play and walks around with a toy for most of the day.  Her foster mom says the minute she gets home River bounds towards her with excitement! 

River would do best in a home with kids over the age of 10.  Although she is VERY gentle, she is a bundle of energy, so we wouldn't want her to knock a little person down in play.  We would like to see River go to a home with a fenced yard so she can run and play  to her hearts content!

This sweet girl is housebroken and knows basic commands.  She is very intelligent and eager to learn.   She is approximately  2 years old and 55 pounds but slightly underweight so would welcome some extra treats . If you want a loyal best friend, to get lots of kisses and are up for playing fetch, reach out to learn more about this precious girl.  

To apply to adopt River, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 


-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary.

Jack is a handsome 2-year old Pit Bull Terrier mix.  He weighs in around 45 pounds and is neutered, current on all his vaccines and has regularly received his Heartworm and Flea preventatives. Jack was adopted from a local shelter into a home with small children but he is a bit of a 'resource guarder' (toys, food) and plays too roughly with the kids. The family tells us Jack is a sweet boy, but gets a little 'mouthy' when excited. This could be worked on with some redirecting exercises. 
He would do best in a home without kids or if there are kids, older ones. They want him to go to a great home and are offering to donate food and heartworm and flea/tick medications to his adopters.

animal.description:
Whiskey is a handsome 3 1/2 year old 50 pound Cattle Dog/Australian Shepherd mix with a gorgeous silky golden coat. He loves to play fetch and also good at just hanging out. He likes to ride in the car and go adventures. One of his favorites things is going through the McDonald drive through for cheeseburgers.

He came to DSDA with a dislocated right elbow. He had surgery to repair the elbow so able to keep his leg. But he doesnt let it slow him down.

Whiskey is a special boy and requires a specific home. He needs an experienced owner and will be happiest as only dog in the home. He loves to go for walks so an active owner is a must. He prefers women over men, but a home with a couple would be fine as long as the woman is home a lot and the man is patient. Whiskey's dream is a fenced yard with trees full of squirrels. 

Read more about Whiskey on Whiskey's Blog Post.

If you are looking for a gorgeous dog that has all the quirks and will keep you on your toes then Whiskey might just be the dog for you!

To meet Whiskey visit us at www.dsda.org/adopt for additional information regarding our adoption criteria and submit our online adoption application.

* Adoption Fees:

Puppies (under 12 months) - $325 (includes tax)
Dogs (12 months and over) - $275 (includes tax)

* Home visits and vet checks are required.

 * If you are interested in meeting one of our dogs, please fill out the online adoption application at www.dsda.org/adopt. 

Qualifications for Adoption: No dog is alike and each dog has different requirements based on breed, age, energy level and life experiences. DSDA is very careful to place our dogs in homes that we believe are the best fit for the dog based on our experience with each dog. All of our dogs live in foster homes which allows us the opportunity to learn about their individual needs. 


	
	Must be 21 years or older with identification showing present address.
	
	
	Must have the knowledge and consent of all adults living in the household.
	
	
	Vet checks are required. All resident animals must be spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations and on monthly heartworm and flea/tick preventative (if applicable).
	
	
	Must receive proof of pet deposit and lease allowing pets if renting.
	
	
	Willingness and capacity to spend the time and money necessary to provide training, medical treatment and responsible care for a pet.
	
	
	Applicant is home more than not.
	
	
	Home visit is required. For this reason, we only adopt locally in the DFW area. Any poisonous plants must be removed from the yard before the home visit.

animal.description:
*PLEASE NOTE:  We do not adopt out on a first-come/first-serve basis.  Applications are accepted for a dog and then a home check is scheduled.  If there are multiple applications for a dog, after all home checks are done,  the dog is adopted out to the home that is the best fit for that dog.
 
 ******Chicagoland Dog Rescue reserves the right to restrict adoption of a dog to potential adopters who live within a fifty (50) mile radius of Schaumburg, IL *****

Hello to my new person/family!!!! My name is Rocket and my whole world has been turned upside down!  My beloved human parents have both passed away and I don’t get along with the resident canine at my current foster home.  A new home where I could be the center of attention would be amazing!   My foster parents say I am a truly lovable dog.  I am happy to cuddle on the bed or the couch but am just as happy to snooze quietly in my dog bed.  I am an empathetic soul who knows when someone is upset and will come right over to snuggle them to help them feel better.  I am also a pretty playful guy but I must admit that I LOVE to swim.  I think that is the lab in me!!!!  I would be an all around great companion for walks, cuddles, swimming and other adventures.  I will come to my new family housebroken, up to date on shots, neutered and ready to share an abundance of love!  If you would like to meet me, please send an email or fill out a pre adoption application and a CDR volunteer will get back to just as quick as they can!
Snuggles and tail wags-Rocket



**The ADOPTION FEE for this pet is $400-450.00,  which includes getting the puppy/dog up to date on rabies, distemper and bordetella vaccines, fecal test and deworming if necessary, heartworm test, spay or neuter (not including pre-surgical bloodwork) and a microchip. Free access to our weekly training classes is also included for the life of the dog, something no other rescue in the area offers.***

animal.description:
***We appreciate your interest in adopting a pug in need. Please respect our process and our time, as we are all volunteers with full time jobs.  An application starts the process.  We are not able to answer calls with questions about the foster pugs. ***

Hi, I am Hendrix, a 10 year old handsome black pug. Are you a homebody? Love to hang out on the couch and read, maybe watch some Netflix? If so, you might be my perfect person!  I just want to hang out with someone who leads a calm lifestyle, likes to snuggle, and will take naps with me.  You see, I’m also quiet, and I am deaf, but I get around inside my house just fine. I am a very good sleeper and I am told I snore quite loudly! 
 
My foster mom calls me “happy go lucky” and very gentle. She thinks I’m funny because I love to kiss her all over her face, but if she leans into kiss me, I lean backwards!  Foster mom does make me wear Man Pants (belly band!) because there is another male dog here in my foster home, and I mark because of it. It’s okay if you have a female sibling for me, or want me to be an “only child.” If you think we’d be perfect friends, please apply for me, Hendrix!

***We encourage you to come to our adoption events to meet the pugs in person if you are interested in adoption. Again, please do not call regarding the adoptable pugs.  APARN is an all volunteer non-profit organization. We do not have a shelter. Our dogs are currently being fostered in private homes generally located throughout the greater Phoenix metro area.***

animal.description:
This sweet girl is Lemon. She was picked up as a stray and sadly her owners were never located. Lemon is a 2 year old Bully mix who weighs around 50 lbs. She’s as sweet as they come. She’s great with all size dogs and children. She’s playful and very loving. She will make a great family pup. She is utd, hw neg (tested below detectable levels) and will be spayed before placement! 


All dogs have a $175 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter! Puppies will be altered before adoption. All rescues and shelters practice pediatric spay and neuter. This is essential in our rescue efforts and it is a policy that we will stick by. All dogs over 8 weeks and 2 pounds will be altered before adoption. There are no exceptions to this rule on all healthy and adoptable dogs. 

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Meet Carrie!
Carrie is about 2 yrs old and weighs about 50 lbs.

Carrie is from a shelter in Tennessee where she had been taken in after being abandoned by her people.  The county she came from has Breed Specific Legislation and she is not welcome there...not even in a loving home.  

The shelter was so overwhelming with all those dogs barking!  She would do best in a home where she can be the one and only and the center of attention! A home with bully breed experience is a plus!

She's super loving with people and really enjoys snuggling.  She is housebroken and crate trained.    

Carrie arrived Heartworm positive and is almost finished with her treatment. 
She has about 2 more weeks of "rest", meaning no running or exercise that elevates her heart rate.  After that, she will be ready to take on the world! 
 
Carrie is available for our Foster to Adopt program.  Foster to Adopt families have the first option to adopt if you determine this is the pup right for you!  

While you foster, we pay all expenses from vetting, to food and we provide a crate, leash, collars, and toys. Your family provides love (something she really needs!) and a safe place to lay her head until she finds her forever home. 

Please email foster@safehavendogil.org for a foster application or additional details.

animal.description:
Meet Gracie... This little lady was surrendered to a boarding facility after her owner passed away. She is a Jack Russell mix who is around 10 years old and 23 lbs. Gracie is a friendly girl. She’s great with all size dogs but if too active and get in her face will give a warning that’s too much. She’s mellow and loves to lounge and nap. She walks great on a leash and does still like walks and to explore the outdoor. She does well in the house and crate. She doesn’t mind the car and is a pretty good all around girl. She does have a few “old lady small growths” as our vet likes to call them that aren’t causing her any issue and our vet doesn’t see reason for concern. He would rather leave them and wait until she needs to be sedated for something else and then discuss removing if needed at that time. She is utd, hw neg (tested below detectable levels) and spayed. 

All dogs have a $175 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter! Puppies will be altered before adoption. All rescues and shelters practice pediatric spay and neuter. This is essential in our rescue efforts and it is a policy that we will stick by. All dogs over 8 weeks and 2 pounds will be altered before adoption. There are no exceptions to this rule on all healthy and adoptable dogs. 

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Oddy (we pronounce it OH DEE)

6-7 years

Male ~40 pounds

Fawn with natural ears and tail

Heart worm negative | neutered 2 October

Available immediately

Oddy is a spunky little boxer mix who steals the heart of all he meets. He was abandoned at a high-kill shelter in Alabama with three siblings, but OBBR pulled him, and he's been getting his much-deserved royal treatment since arriving in Georgia! He's being treated for worms (not heart worm), will be neutered soon, and will undoubtedly wiggle his way into the perfect home soon.

Oddy has been great with a male, foster fur-sibling but also shown fence aggression with the neighboring dog who instigates. After being guided away from the fence that first time, he learned quickly not to engage. He is intelligent and has picked up on house rules very quickly.

This sweet guy would love to be with a family who can dote on him, as he's usually nearby waiting for your affection. He would sure like to be your lap dog if you allow it. He is house-trained, does fine in a crate, and is well-behaved in free roam. He knows "sit", "down" and is learning "stay". He even lays down before receiving his food bowl! Like many boxers around the world, he's very free with sweet boxer kisses.

Does this sound like a fella you could love? If so, you can submit an application to adopt at
www.obbrescue.org.
Adoption fee is $275.00. To apply to adopt Oddy, visit our website at

animal.description: If youre looking for the perfect mix of sugar, spice, and everything nice - Abigail is your girl! This spunky little nugget refuses to let her disability stop her from enjoying every minute of each day. She is a 4 year old terrier mix who weighs around 35 pounds. Originally, she was found on the side of the road in rough shape with several broken bones. Due to the extent of her injuries, she has since had her front leg and a few of her toes removed. She now rocks a super fashionable cart as needed so she never misses out on a thing. Abigail enjoys the company of other dogs but due to her sensitive nature, she prefers calm, well socialized, and non-reactive pups. Her ideal home would be one with only one other dog as she can get overwhelmed easily around other animals. *No cats* for this gal as she tends to chase her fellow feline friends. Being a pup who doesnt always remember she has a disability, Abigail would benefit from a family who is home often and can watch over her to ensure her safety. She does best with children 13+ and older as she still has that puppy-like nature and can a rambunctious goofball at times. There is never a bad day with Abigail; its always smiles, laughs, and endless kisses. She is a real gem and without a doubt, a one of a kind pup. This very special little girl has a heart of gold and deserves a fun-loving family to share her life with. If you own your home in either Volusia, Lake, Orange, Seminole, or Osceola county FL with a fenced in yard and would like to meet Abigail, please fill out an adoption screening form: https://mettarescuefamily.org/adoptable-dogs

animal.description:
Hi there Im Pearl but my foster family calls me Pearly Jane. Im estimated to be 9 years old and Im a long haired Chihuahua. My foster family rescued me from the Pasadena Shelter after I outwore my welcome, also known as a stray hold. YES, I was found as a stray! I can hardly believe it myself. I am sweet, extremely quiet and I hardly make any messes. My favorite past times are, napping and eating and napping some more. I am potty pad trained when Im in my kennel and I love to do my business outside. When I nap I sometimes have issues controlling my bladder so a waterproof bed and small throw blankets keep my space easy to clean. 

The vet feels that I was a breeder dog cast off when my past life caught up to me. All the litters of babies have weakened my bladder, I have had extensive dental work and my mammary tumors have been removed. My family knows that not everyone will want an older girl with bedtime potty issues so they are committed to keeping me safe until the RIGHT family comes along. I know that there is a family out there that can accept me as the perfectly imperfect girl I am and LOVE me to the end of my days. If youd like to have a quiet girl that just wants to snuggle and love you until the end of her days, thats me!

If interested in adoption, the first step is to visit our website chipnsnip.org to complete our adoption application! All current pets in the home must be up to date on vaccinations, heartworm preventatives and altered unless medically unfit. Our approval process includes an approved application, reference check, home visit and once approved, a meet and greet with the dog. Applicant must live within a 3 hour radius of the Houston Area to adopt.

animal.description:
Boomer is a special dog looking for a patient, loving family! He came to Foothills Humane Society with his two sisters in January of 2019.  All three were very under-socialized and had little contact with humans. It took time for us to earn their trust. Boomer was the most frightened and just sat in the corner shaking. 

Boomer now loves going for walks with people he knows and has become confident enough to lead, but he always checks in with you. It was pretty scary for him to go for walks without another dog, but he's now mastered that! He has a funny sense of humor and likes to steal his sister’s toys and hide them, but doesn’t mind if she takes them back! He loves to play chase with other dogs and his trusted human friends! He is still extremely shy with new people, but after meeting you a few times he comes around. 

Boomer is looking for a quiet, low drama home (without children under the age of 12) with an outgoing dog friend or two, a fenced yard, and people that will give him a little time to settle in and get used to a big change! As comfortable as he has gotten with us, he will need time to adjust to a new home. It would be best if you lived fairly close and could commit to at least 2-3 visits. His trainer will provide 3 free sessions to introduce him and go over the best ways to acclimate him to your home. If you are think that you are a good fit for Boomer, please fill out an adoption application online through our website, foothillshumanesociety.org.

animal.description:
S.P.C.A. Albrecht Center For Animal Welfare
 Requirements for Adoption
1. Most of our dogs will require a fenced in yard to allow them to play safely outdoors.
2. If you have other pets in the home, you will need to provide proof of current rabies vaccines.
3. If you rent your home, we will need to verify that you have your landlord’s approval for the pet.
4. If you have other pets, we strongly encourage you to bring them to the shelter to meet the animal you wish to adopt first, to make sure everyone will get along.
The S.P.C.A. Albrecht Center for Animale Welfare adoption fees vary. Please call the shelter for each pet's adoption fee. 803-648-6863. Adoption fees include age-appropriate vaccinations, deworming, spay/neuter and microchip implantation and registration. Heartworm testing and treatment is also included for adult dogs. love
