animal.description:
Are you a foodie? Because our gorgeous girl Rayna is! With her beautiful auburn and white coat, she resembles a piece of pumpkin pie with whipped cream on top. Rayna is as sweet as pie too, minus all the sugar and calories. She'll be on her best behavior as she is house trained. Rayna is playful but is also a firm believer in taking naps so adopt her today and have a forever food coma buddy!

Rayna is about 3 years old and weighs about 51 pounds.

If you're interested in meeting Rayna, please visit our website to learn about our adoption process and to fill out an application, www.gatewaypets.org/adopt

All of our dogs and cats will be micro-chipped, spayed or neutered, and up-to-date on vaccinations at the time of adoption. For more photos of Rayna, follow us on Facebook Gateway Pet Guardians and Instagram @gatewaypets ... #gpgRayna. 

To view other adoptable pets from our shelter, please visit, www.gatewaypets.org/adopt

Gateway Pet Guardians is proud to offer a variety of mixed breed dogs available for adoption. However, please keep in mind that we rarely know the genetic background of the animals we rescue and, as such, we cannot guarantee the exact breed combinations found within this dog. However, we do not know his/her actual genetic makeup. Just know that this dog is probably a variety of several different breeds that have combined to create one very amazing and unique animal.

Ziggy is approximately 5 years old (born in August of 2016), weighs in at 64 pounds, with a lot of personality!!! He's an awesome guy... big and strong and in need of an owner who will give him the leadership and consistency he needs. He is high energy and needs an active adopter who can keep up with him and has a desire to find ways to keep Ziggy engaged and active. A large fenced yard is recommended. Ziggy. Ziggy would do best in a home as the only pet and with no small children. He does have a high prey drive so we recommend a pinch collar for walking. He's very receptive to training and will thrive with a routine and exercise commitment. Ziggy loves to jump up and say hi to you. The staff is teaching him to sit for leashing and unleashing. He is doing very will and is willing to learn to be the best boy ever!

Adopt Don't Shop!

If you love the big boys... come to our Palm City facility and meet Ziggy. You will fall in love! Ziggy's adoption fee is sponsored by our wonderful board members. He will also go home with a goody bag donated from Conair. Let's give Ziggy the happy ending he deserves!

animal.description: Winnie came into our rescue about 5 years ago when we received a call about a dog having issues giving brith. When we got to where Winnie was it was obvious she was in major trouble, she was rushed to the vet where she wasn't expected to survive. The vet thought Winnie had been in labor for about 3 days but the first puppy was stuck and had died. Needless to say Winnie had a raging infection and the surgery itself was risky. But Winnie pulled through the surgery like the trooper she is. Winnie has probably never been around people until we rescued her so she is slow to trust strangers but once she does she is a super sweet girl. It took her 6 months to learn to trust her foster mom. Winnie loves to play fetch and play with the other dogs in her foster home. Winnie would do best in a home with at least one other dog and older kids. Winnie will need time to adjust to her new home and new environment. She is spayed, up to date on shots, housebroken, and crate trained.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Aleu seems very friendly with most dogs, Aleu I think is an escape artist. She was very interested in the fence. I think she is a bit fearful but more likely was not out and about much in her prior life. I would not rule out having been dumped. She seems to have been an indoor dog. She is very clingy, probably has some separation anxiety. She also seems to be a bit of a watch dog. I left the door from the garage open to the dog run. She let the neighbors know she was there. She is very petite, only 41 pounds. She could put on a few more pounds but around 45pounds is probably good for her. Her fearfulness is not the typical shyness of hybrids, it is simply the fearfulness of a dog that has not experienced much in life. She seems very sweet.

Aleu is probably not suitable for a family with rambunctious kids but I do not see shyness in her, just fearfulness. There is a difference. Oh, she likes food. Seems to have had little training. We walked to the mailbox and after a few tugs on the halter already reacted by not pulling as hard. She seems to be a very nice dog. The pictures do not do her justice. She is cute

Aleu is not shy, not fearful, just very untrained, probably back yard dog, allowed in house but ZERO training. Most likely was also caught in traffic, very fearful of moving cars.

animal.description: Coral came to us from Ohio in need of medical care. Her bloodwork was a little off so she went straight from the shelter to Noah's in Indianapolis to get all checked over. She stayed overnight then was released to her temporary foster mom and she will be rechecked this week to see what we are looking at, medical wise. Depending on her recheck and the results of testing, she could possibly be moved to the forever foster status. We will keep you updated on Coral as we hear from the clinic on her condition.10/21 UPDATE: Coral saw Dr. Mark at Noah's last week for a brief check over after starting her medications. She went in yesterday to have her bloodwork rechecked, we are waiting on the results of that and will update ASAP :)11/28 UPDATE: After several weeks of vet rechecks, bloodwork rechecks and being on the right medications for her needs, Coral is feeling MUCH better and her bloodwork numbers have improved!! She will have another bloodwork recheck on December 2nd and if her platelets have continued to go up, we feel that Coral will be ready to find her longer term foster, forever foster or adoptive home!! Once her platelets are leveled off, she will be off of the Prednisone. She will need to be on the Mycophenalate for life. From her current foster mom: Coral is a sweet 8 year old girl (approx) and is around 60 lb. She is quiet most of the time, except when there is food involved, then she can get a little antsy and wants you to share :) She is good at letting you know when her water bowl is empty and if she needs to go potty. She was a little distant at the beginning but as she gets more comfortable, she follows me everywhere and sometimes likes to sleep next to you on the couch. She has some medical issues, mostly an autoimmune disease, she is currently taking prednisone (twice a day) and an Immunosuppressive (Mycophenolate, every 8 hours). Her current routine is breakfast around 7:30am, with the morning pills (Prednisone and Mycphenolate). A cookie around 10am. Some treats around her foster mom's lunch time. Then Mycophenolate around 3 pm. Some treats in the afternoon depending how she is behaving :) Dinner is around 7pm together with the Prednisone. And around 10:30pm she takes her Mycphenolate and goes to bed. She may need to go potty in the middle of the night (side effects of the Prednisone). She sleeps on her kennel (door open) sometimes or just on a bed close to foster mom. She wasn't super fond of the kennel at the beginning but she knows now that the place she goes when foster mom is not in the house. Oh, and she has GREAT time/distance coordination, be sure to watch her treat-catching video!!
animal.name: Coral - MEDICAL NEEDS!!

animal.description:
Winston
Male
Long Haired Dachshund mix
Born 2018

Contact Kate at kmolsbe@gmail.com for more information about Winston.

When little Winston came to NMAF out of a rural shelter, he had no hair on the backs of his ears or along his spine.  The shelter thought he had some form of skin disease so had marked him to only be handled with gloves.  He was very frightened, terribly thin, but sweet in nature.  An exam by a local vet thought he was actually part Chinese Crested, so that is how we listed him.  In the few weeks since he has come into foster care, with good nutrition and a calm & loving environment, his coat has begun to grow back in all the bare spots.  A second evaluation by Dr. Martin at VCA-Wyoming told us he is not Chinese Crested, so hence his change in breed.  Little Winston has blossomed in foster care - he is a happy and playful little guy (still under 9 pounds but putting on needed weight) and enjoys his buddy Billie a lot.  He is not good at sharing his foster mom and is protective of his food bowl, so if he finds a Furever Home with another dog, his family will need to be aware of that.  We believe he could also be an only dog as long as he can have access to other dogs through family or friends to play with. He prefers dogs near his own size and who like to play.

Winston still needs to be neutered and that will happen on November 10th (vet clinics are still backed up for spay/neuters...), but he could go to his Furever Home before that if his family is willing to bring him for his appointment and see him through the surgery recovery.  He is up-to-date on all shots and microchipped.  He has had his heartworm test and it was negative.

If you are interested in meeting Winston, please complete an application, found at www.nmaf.org/adopt/adoption-application, and email it to dogs@nmaf.org.  There is no commitment or guarantee for adoption, but your application allows for screening before setting up a meet & greet with his foster.

Because home visits are required, NMAF dogs cannot be adopted out of the greater Albuquerque / Santa Fe area.

Adoption Clinic Location:  PetSmart - Academy & Wyoming, Saturdays, 10:00 a.m. - 1:00 p.m. - Currently Suspended

Please visit our website at www.nmaf.org for more information.

Meet Cliff. ?

Cliff is now looking for his forever home! Cliff is a lean muscular guy who is looking for someone to give him the boundaries he needs. It’s apparent that Cliff hasn’t been given a set of rules and needs to be taught most good dog manners. He knows sit and that is currently it. He is willing to learn with some good treats involved! Cliff does tend to pull on a leash, and would be suggested he has a harness in his new home. Cliff will need a confined yard either by fence or appropriate tie out. (Or someone who is responsible to go out with him on a leash every time). Cliff needs a strong leader / owner to learn his respected boundaries. Additionally Cliff does tend to mark as he is not neutered. We suspect this will be lessened or stopped with his neuter.

animal.description:
Happy news!!  We are banding together and collabbing with our good friends at @puppykittynycity to help this darling dog find his forever!!  Teamwork makes the dream work as we know. One team one mission is the rule we live by!

Ohhh Papa Elf ? What a cute boy and yet not ONE inquiry ? He sits and waits for the phone to ring but all he hears is silence ? We don’t understand why!  Is it because he’s 8? Eight is a great age!  Still lively and fun loving yet also lives to relax!  Papa was pulled from the NYACC in December of 2019 where he was found as a stray.  The city shelter is not no-kill... he just had to be saved!!  Pops is about 60 pounds so a medium size and he currently is lucky to be in a Foster home ?

Papa Elf is ok on leash, he does get happily excited when he sees people so he may jump up to greet you, but his foster peeps are working on that. Once he knows he’s safe, he’s loving and he has lots of energy to play. He sleeps in his crate like a good boy and his favorite toy is a ducky!!  He adores rolling around in the grass and listens to commands. 

Papa gets along with other dogs and a proper intro is mandatory to be set up for success!  He’s not a fan of kitties (his loss lol). Mr. Elf will do best in a home that is consisent with rules - he thrives with a strong leader.  He’s neutered, up to date on vaccines and housebroken. He is doing so wonderful with all the structure he now has!! 

Why oh why is this boy still homeless? He matters just like they all do. Do you have a space in your home and heart to make his dreams come true?  Please email us at info@tufftails.org for the full scoopage. You not only will make this boy’s life complete, but you may be a changed person yourself knowing you are this guy’s hero ?? Thank you!! xo

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Petey's story will tug at your heartstrings, as he has been through so much! Petey was originally adopted from our shelter when he was a puppy, back in 2014. His adopter told us that at the time, we had warned her that he had baggage, having been mistreated by a man, and that he was unable to forget that part of his life. However, they loved him deeply and worked through the problems he had with males, and showed us that he had learned to accept gentleness and love from all sexes. Petey was loved by his adoptive family for six years, but when the family relocated to a part of the country where they were not permitted to have a pit bull, they brought him back to our shelter so we could find him another wonderful home, back in October, 2020. Dogs like Petey defy the classic mistaken generalizations the breed often garners, and we were thrilled that a family who spotted him on a rescue site visited the shelter, and fell in love. Fast forward to January 30--the adoptive family took Petey to their family vet for a minor issue with one of his toenails, and were told by the vet that Petey had arthritis in his hips, and also has a significant heart murmur. They felt they couldn't give Petey what he needed, and brought him immediately back to the County Shelter for rehoming. Petey is such a gentle boy! He loves babies, children of all ages, cats, and other dogs. He adores women and is most comfortable with women, but accepts males as well, when he is given a bit of space. He is beautifully housetrained-and what wonderful manners he has! He walks beautifully on a leash, and as far as training, he does a beautiful sit, down, gives paw, gives other paw, and is just all in all a perfect dog. He is neutered, current with his vaccines, microchipped, and appreciates love. Of course, more than anything else, Petey will appreciate a home where he can get over his sense of loss, and be given time to adjust to a new routine. Can you give him that, despite his medical needs? We don't expect miraculous cures from our adopters--we want people to love our dogs and cats, and do the best they can for them. Petey is currently in a foster home with cats, two small dogs, a teen boy, and a sweet working-from-home mom! Apply to adopt here: friendsofcampbellcounty.org, under the animals heading. #lovemesomepetey #shelterpets #savealife

PLEASE NOTE: This pet has been posted by Friends of Campbell County Animal Control, Rustburg, VA. For questions about the pet, please email us at FOACinfo@gmail.com. All adoptions begin with an application, found under the "Animals" tab on our website, friendsofcampbellcounty.org. *We do not promote dog adoptions to homes where an invisible fence is the fencing of choice.
